WEBVTT

00:36.120 --> 00:39.320
[♪♪♪]

00:44.640 --> 00:46.080
NEWSCASTER:
<i>The woman who inspired</i>

00:46.080 --> 00:47.920
<i>the songwriter</i>
<i>and poet Leonard Cohen</i>

00:47.920 --> 00:50.760
<i>to write some of his</i>
<i>best-known work has died.</i>

00:50.760 --> 00:52.200
<i>"So Long, Marianne"</i>

00:52.200 --> 00:54.360
<i>and "Bird on a Wire"</i>
<i>were written decades ago</i>

00:54.360 --> 00:57.160
<i>for Cohen's then-lover</i>
<i>and muse, Marianne Ihlen.</i>

00:57.160 --> 00:59.520
<i>They split up,</i>
<i>but when Marianne grew ill</i>

00:59.520 --> 01:00.960
<i>and near death with leukemia,</i>

01:00.960 --> 01:03.720
<i>her close friend</i>
<i>Jan Christian Mollestad</i>

01:03.720 --> 01:05.680
<i>contacted Leonard Cohen.</i>

01:05.680 --> 01:08.200
<i>Less than two hours later,</i>
<i>a message came back,</i>

01:08.200 --> 01:09.840
<i>which Jan read to her.</i>

01:11.280 --> 01:13.320
MOLLESTAD [ON RECORDING]:
<i>"Dearest Marianne.</i>

01:13.320 --> 01:15.520
<i>I'm just a little behind you.</i>

01:15.520 --> 01:18.560
<i>Close enough</i>
<i>to take your hand.</i>

01:18.560 --> 01:21.680
<i>I've never forgotten</i>
<i>your love and your beauty.</i>

01:21.680 --> 01:24.920
<i>But you know that.</i>
<i>I don't have to say more.</i>

01:26.040 --> 01:28.600
<i>Well, safe travels, old friend.</i>

01:29.520 --> 01:31.680
<i>See you down the road.</i>

01:31.680 --> 01:35.800
<i>Endless love and gratitude,</i>
<i>your Leonard."</i>

01:39.760 --> 01:41.360
[CROWD CHEERING, APPLAUDING]

01:49.320 --> 01:51.880
I wrote this for Marianne.

01:51.880 --> 01:54.560
I hope she's here.
Maybe she's here.

01:56.840 --> 01:59.240
I hope she's here.

01:59.240 --> 02:00.760
Marianne.

02:02.560 --> 02:05.520
This song is called
"So Long, Marianne."

02:05.520 --> 02:10.640
And a girl called Marianne
that I know very well,

02:10.640 --> 02:13.960
she came to me after I sang it
for her first, and she said--

02:13.960 --> 02:16.200
She's a Norwegian.
She said, uh,

02:16.200 --> 02:19.640
"I'm certainly glad that song
wasn't written for me."

02:19.640 --> 02:21.800
I said, "Oh, uh, yeah?"

02:21.800 --> 02:25.040
And she said, "Yeah,
'cause my name is 'Marionn-eh.'"

02:25.040 --> 02:27.320
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

02:30.920 --> 02:34.360
♪<i> Come over to the window</i> ♪

02:34.360 --> 02:37.320
♪<i> My little darlin'</i> ♪

02:41.280 --> 02:46.560
♪<i> I'd like to try</i>
<i>To read your palm</i> ♪

02:50.600 --> 02:55.880
♪<i> I used to think I was</i>
<i>Some kind of gypsy boy</i> ♪

02:59.240 --> 03:03.760
♪<i> Before I let you</i>
<i>Take me home...</i> ♪

03:05.240 --> 03:08.600
[♪♪♪]

03:08.600 --> 03:12.120
BROOMFIELD:
<i>This is Marianne,</i>
<i>filmed on the island of Hydra</i>

03:12.120 --> 03:14.040
<i>in the early '60s.</i>

03:14.040 --> 03:16.360
<i>She said the song</i>
<i>"So Long, Marianne"</i>

03:16.360 --> 03:18.640
<i>was originally called</i>
<i>"Come On, Marianne"</i>

03:18.640 --> 03:21.640
<i>and was not</i>
<i>her favorite song.</i>

03:21.640 --> 03:25.080
<i>She said it was not originally</i>
<i>intended as a goodbye,</i>

03:25.080 --> 03:27.800
<i>but came, in actuality,</i>
<i>to foreshadow the end</i>

03:27.800 --> 03:31.640
<i>of Marianne and Leonard's</i>
<i>relationship as lovers.</i>

03:33.120 --> 03:37.040
<i>This is Little Axel,</i>
<i>Marianne's 7-year-old son.</i>

03:37.040 --> 03:38.560
Film it.
COHEN: It looks like

03:38.560 --> 03:40.160
some kind of a lobster.

03:40.160 --> 03:43.000
It has all kinds of...

03:43.000 --> 03:46.920
<i>It was the '60s, and the time</i>
<i>of free love and open marriage,</i>

03:46.920 --> 03:49.720
<i>including</i>
<i>Leonard and Marianne's.</i>

03:49.720 --> 03:53.440
<i>I was a rather lost 20-year-old</i>
<i>visiting the island of Hydra</i>

03:53.440 --> 03:55.760
<i>when Marianne</i>
<i>befriended me.</i>

03:55.760 --> 03:59.720
<i>For a short while,</i>
<i>I became one of her lovers.</i>

03:59.720 --> 04:02.000
<i>She encouraged me</i>
<i>to follow my dreams,</i>

04:02.000 --> 04:03.960
<i>and she played me</i>
<i>Leonard's songs</i>

04:03.960 --> 04:05.680
<i>under the Greek moon and stars.</i>

04:05.680 --> 04:09.120
<i>Her smile and enthusiasm</i>
<i>were one-of-a-kind,</i>

04:09.120 --> 04:11.120
<i>and I felt</i>
<i>completely intoxicated</i>

04:11.120 --> 04:13.960
<i>by the beauty</i>
<i>of their relationship.</i>

04:17.200 --> 04:18.960
COHEN:
<i>I just left one day.</i>

04:18.960 --> 04:23.360
<i>And, uh, I won a prize</i>
<i>for a book that I wrote.</i>

04:23.360 --> 04:24.960
<i>And they gave me some money,</i>

04:24.960 --> 04:27.840
<i>and I got on a plane.</i>

04:27.840 --> 04:31.400
<i>I came eventually to, uh--</i>
<i>To Greece</i>

04:31.400 --> 04:33.120
<i>and got on a boat.</i>

04:33.120 --> 04:36.200
<i>And I just saw this island that</i>
<i>was so beautiful, you know?</i>

04:36.200 --> 04:37.480
<i>I'd come from a country</i>

04:37.480 --> 04:39.360
<i>that's covered with snow</i>
<i>half the year.</i>

04:39.360 --> 04:43.360
<i>And I saw this island,</i>
<i>you know, completely shining.</i>

04:43.360 --> 04:46.040
<i>I just got off,</i>
<i>met a girl there,</i>

04:46.040 --> 04:47.760
<i>and I stayed.</i>

04:51.880 --> 04:55.000
<i>There were just a few</i>
<i>foreigners there in those days.</i>

04:55.000 --> 04:58.160
<i>And the Johnstons were,</i>
<i>um, central figures.</i>

04:58.160 --> 05:00.280
<i>They were older,</i>
<i>they were doing</i>

05:00.280 --> 05:02.560
<i>what we all wanted to do,</i>
<i>which was to write</i>

05:02.560 --> 05:04.560
<i>and to make</i>
<i>a living out of writing.</i>

05:04.560 --> 05:08.680
<i>And they were there,</i>
<i>and they were very wonderful,</i>

05:08.680 --> 05:10.480
<i>colorful, hospitable people.</i>

05:10.480 --> 05:14.720
<i>And they helped me settle in.</i>
<i>They really helped me out.</i>

05:14.720 --> 05:20.200
WOMAN:
<i>That was first what made him</i>
<i>an outcast in Montreal.</i>

05:20.200 --> 05:23.040
<i>It was the journey</i>
<i>into the dark,</i>

05:23.040 --> 05:26.160
<i>because nobody</i>
<i>wanted to go there.</i>

05:26.160 --> 05:28.680
<i>And I remember</i>
<i>my mother writing me</i>

05:28.680 --> 05:31.280
<i>some horrible things</i>
<i>about him.</i>

05:31.280 --> 05:34.560
<i>He knew the dark.</i>
<i>He knew the struggle</i>

05:34.560 --> 05:37.200
<i>from moment to moment.</i>

05:37.200 --> 05:40.520
<i>You were supposed to</i>
<i>find a mate</i>

05:40.520 --> 05:44.920
<i>and get married</i>
<i>and live in Westmount.</i>

05:44.920 --> 05:48.040
<i>They all stayed in Westmount.</i>

05:48.040 --> 05:50.560
<i>So we... We left.</i>

05:50.560 --> 05:53.360
<i>We had our own way of being.</i>

05:53.360 --> 05:55.720
<i>We found our own lives,</i>

05:55.720 --> 05:59.800
<i>but they turned out</i>
<i>to be synchronistic.</i>

06:01.000 --> 06:02.840
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

06:07.760 --> 06:10.880
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>When I first went to Hydra,</i>

06:10.880 --> 06:17.440
<i>I was running away</i>
<i>because I couldn't cope.</i>

06:17.440 --> 06:19.920
<i>And in many ways Leonard</i>
<i>was also looking</i>

06:19.920 --> 06:22.600
<i>for something different.</i>

06:22.600 --> 06:25.600
<i>So there we were, two refugees,</i>
<i>running away from something</i>

06:25.600 --> 06:31.320
<i>I knew I'd eventually</i>
<i>have to face.</i>

06:31.320 --> 06:34.120
[IN ENGLISH]
Can I have a sip?

06:34.120 --> 06:36.400
You'll have to even
all of them.

06:38.600 --> 06:42.880
<i>When I first saw Leonard,</i>

06:42.880 --> 06:46.560
<i>I was standing in the shop</i>
<i>with my basket.</i>

06:46.560 --> 06:49.640
<i>He was standing in the doorway</i>
<i>with the sun behind him.</i>

06:49.640 --> 06:52.400
<i>I could only see</i>
<i>his silhouette.</i>

06:52.400 --> 06:55.000
<i>Then he said,</i>

06:55.000 --> 06:58.200
[IN ENGLISH]
<i>"Would you like to join us?</i>
<i>We're sitting outside."</i>

06:58.200 --> 07:02.480
[IN NORWEGIAN]
<i>I remember</i>
<i>my eyes met his eyes.</i>

07:02.480 --> 07:05.680
<i>I felt it</i>
<i>throughout my whole body.</i>

07:05.680 --> 07:07.720
<i>It was incredible.</i>

07:07.720 --> 07:10.560
<i>The first year</i>
<i>on Hydra was fantastic,</i>

07:10.560 --> 07:13.280
<i>and he just wrote and wrote.</i>

07:13.280 --> 07:18.480
<i>I ran and did the shopping</i>
<i>and brought food.</i>

07:18.480 --> 07:23.120
<i>And I was his Greek muse,</i>
<i>who sat at his feet.</i>

07:23.120 --> 07:25.600
<i>He was the creative one.</i>

07:25.600 --> 07:27.640
COHEN:
<i>The days were</i>
<i>very, very ordinary.</i>

07:27.640 --> 07:30.160
<i>We'd get up early</i>
<i>and have breakfast,</i>

07:30.160 --> 07:31.880
<i>and I'd go to work.</i>

07:31.880 --> 07:35.440
<i>And, uh, a sandwich</i>
<i>would be brought to me.</i>

07:35.440 --> 07:38.720
<i>I think I was on speed too,</i>
<i>so I wasn't eating very much.</i>

07:38.720 --> 07:41.960
<i>And, uh, that's-- The day</i>
<i>would proceed like that.</i>

07:41.960 --> 07:44.440
<i>I had a quota. I think</i>
<i>it was three pages a day.</i>

07:46.000 --> 07:50.240
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>Those years were really good.</i>

07:50.240 --> 07:54.680
<i>We sat in the sun, lay in</i>
<i>the sun, walked in the sun.</i>

07:54.680 --> 07:58.560
<i>We listened to music,</i>
<i>we bathed.</i>

07:58.560 --> 08:01.840
<i>We played,</i>
<i>we drank and discussed.</i>

08:01.840 --> 08:04.640
<i>There was writing</i>
<i>and lovemaking.</i>

08:04.640 --> 08:07.040
<i>It was absolutely fabulous.</i>

08:09.240 --> 08:12.400
<i>I never felt</i>
<i>I was much to look at.</i>

08:12.400 --> 08:14.640
<i>I didn't believe Leonard</i>
<i>when he said,</i>

08:14.640 --> 08:17.720
[IN ENGLISH]
<i>"You are the most beautiful</i>
<i>woman I've ever seen."</i>

08:17.720 --> 08:23.200
[IN NORWEGIAN]
<i>I always thought</i>
<i>my face was too round.</i>

08:23.200 --> 08:25.680
<i>So I was walked looking down.</i>

08:25.680 --> 08:28.960
<i>But I did have</i>
<i>sun-bleached hair.</i>

08:28.960 --> 08:33.360
<i>And in Greece,</i>
<i>I was so very blond.</i>

08:34.960 --> 08:37.760
<i>Skinny, almost no boobs.</i>

08:37.760 --> 08:39.120
<i>[CHUCKLES]</i>

08:39.120 --> 08:40.920
<i>To my big regret.</i>

08:41.920 --> 08:44.880
<i>Leonard was beautiful.</i>

08:44.880 --> 08:48.040
<i>But he never thought it.</i>

08:48.040 --> 08:50.560
<i>We both had that problem.</i>

08:50.560 --> 08:53.600
<i>We'd often look in the mirror</i>
<i>before going out</i>

08:53.600 --> 08:55.560
<i>and wonder who we were today.</i>

08:55.560 --> 08:57.800
<i>How strange we could be.</i>

08:59.760 --> 09:01.480
MOLLESTAD:
<i>She was beautiful.</i>

09:01.480 --> 09:04.160
<i>But she didn't really</i>
<i>enjoy being beautiful</i>

09:04.160 --> 09:05.600
<i>before she met Leonard,</i>

09:05.600 --> 09:10.000
<i>and he made her love living.</i>

09:10.000 --> 09:14.840
<i>She felt that not only</i>
<i>did Leonard see her,</i>

09:14.840 --> 09:17.120
<i>but he really loved her</i>

09:17.120 --> 09:21.440
<i>and he really made her</i>
<i>feel beautiful.</i>

09:22.680 --> 09:25.480
[♪♪♪]

09:25.480 --> 09:28.960
<i>I think if you should really</i>
<i>understand Marianne,</i>

09:28.960 --> 09:34.760
<i>you have to understand</i>
<i>her first husband, Axel.</i>

09:34.760 --> 09:38.800
<i>Axel could get so angry.</i>
<i>So he would throw out, uh,</i>

09:38.800 --> 09:43.200
<i>the furniture from the window</i>
<i>and out in the street.</i>

09:43.200 --> 09:46.200
<i>I don't think</i>
<i>he ever hit her,</i>

09:46.200 --> 09:49.080
<i>but he was violent.</i>

09:49.080 --> 09:52.880
<i>Leonard was the one who</i>
<i>came into Marianne's life,</i>

09:52.880 --> 09:59.880
<i>who had watched</i>
<i>the relationship breaking down.</i>

09:59.880 --> 10:01.800
<i>Leonard saved her life,</i>

10:01.800 --> 10:06.760
<i>and he went into a kind of role</i>
<i>as a kind of helping hand.</i>

10:06.760 --> 10:08.920
<i>He helped with Little Axel,</i>

10:08.920 --> 10:13.400
<i>and he helped her with talking</i>
<i>and practical things.</i>

10:14.520 --> 10:19.080
<i>He was the father,</i>
<i>in a real sense.</i>

10:19.080 --> 10:22.840
<i>And Little Axel still</i>
<i>is talking about Leonard</i>

10:22.840 --> 10:25.760
<i>as a very good force.</i>

10:27.800 --> 10:30.040
BROWN:
<i>He was a very smart kid.</i>

10:30.040 --> 10:32.480
<i>He was very quiet.</i>

10:32.480 --> 10:35.120
<i>Maybe a bit shy, even.</i>

10:35.120 --> 10:37.800
<i>Axel and I would just...</i>
<i>We would roam the hills.</i>

10:37.800 --> 10:41.640
<i>We would find fossils and...</i>

10:41.640 --> 10:46.080
GOLDMAN:
<i>I lived there from the time</i>
<i>that I was 3 months old.</i>

10:46.080 --> 10:48.600
<i>We used to run around</i>
<i>barefoot,</i>

10:48.600 --> 10:50.400
<i>with the slightly powdery</i>
<i>feeling</i>

10:50.400 --> 10:54.040
<i>of the dried seawater</i>
<i>on the stones.</i>

10:54.040 --> 10:57.920
<i>Every part of it</i>
<i>is beautiful in every season,</i>

10:57.920 --> 11:00.200
<i>anytime of the day</i>
<i>or night.</i>

11:01.520 --> 11:03.880
The freshly baked bread
and things like that.

11:03.880 --> 11:07.120
I mean, I've never experienced
those things anywhere else.

11:07.120 --> 11:09.920
Even the air has a kind of--
You can sort of feel the air,

11:09.920 --> 11:11.400
especially in the evening.

11:11.400 --> 11:13.800
It feels like sort of
you're wrapped in something

11:13.800 --> 11:15.480
silky and velvety.

11:18.000 --> 11:20.560
<i>There was</i>
<i>so much freedom there</i>

11:20.560 --> 11:23.240
<i>that people just went</i>
<i>too far with it.</i>

11:23.240 --> 11:26.480
<i>So there was always that danger</i>
<i>hanging over people.</i>

11:28.000 --> 11:30.560
BROOMFIELD:
<i>I was mesmerized</i>
<i>by the island's beauty</i>

11:30.560 --> 11:33.920
<i>and had never before met so</i>
<i>many golden, sun-kissed people</i>

11:33.920 --> 11:37.600
<i>of either sex</i>
<i>having so much fun together.</i>

11:37.600 --> 11:41.120
<i>It felt like</i>
<i>anything was possible.</i>

11:41.120 --> 11:43.680
<i>Marianne gave me</i>
<i>my first acid trip,</i>

11:43.680 --> 11:46.240
<i>which she said had come</i>
<i>from a friend of Leonard's</i>

11:46.240 --> 11:48.200
<i>in London called Malcolm,</i>

11:48.200 --> 11:52.280
<i>and she took these pictures</i>
<i>of me the morning after.</i>

11:52.280 --> 11:54.560
<i>I had no intention</i>
<i>of leaving,</i>

11:54.560 --> 11:56.680
<i>but then one</i>
<i>of Marianne's other lovers</i>

11:56.680 --> 11:59.000
<i>unexpectedly showed up</i>
<i>on the island,</i>

11:59.000 --> 12:01.360
<i>and I found myself</i>
<i>hastily boarding</i>

12:01.360 --> 12:04.360
<i>the next boat back to Athens.</i>

12:04.360 --> 12:08.520
<i>My enthusiasm for Hydra,</i>
<i>however, remained undiminished.</i>

12:08.520 --> 12:11.800
<i>I suggested to Rick,</i>
<i>my best friend from school,</i>

12:11.800 --> 12:13.240
<i>that he go there as a break</i>

12:13.240 --> 12:15.800
<i>from a hectic career</i>
<i>as a journalist.</i>

12:15.800 --> 12:18.080
<i>Rick intended to go</i>
<i>for two weeks</i>

12:18.080 --> 12:21.520
<i>but ended up staying</i>
<i>for 14 years.</i>

12:21.520 --> 12:24.240
I came to Hydra,
which he recommended, and, um,

12:24.240 --> 12:27.200
suddenly this enormous
sense of relief,

12:27.200 --> 12:30.360
because it was a combination,
I think, of beauty,

12:30.360 --> 12:33.320
the beauty of the place,
the simplicity of the place,

12:33.320 --> 12:36.080
and the genuineness
of the environment there.

12:36.080 --> 12:38.720
It was just
a small group of artists

12:38.720 --> 12:41.840
<i>who were either refugees</i>
<i>of some kind or another,</i>

12:41.840 --> 12:44.080
<i>and you could live</i>
<i>so cheaply then.</i>

12:44.080 --> 12:46.760
<i>Leonard didn't have</i>
<i>much money back then.</i>

12:46.760 --> 12:48.680
<i>And there was</i>
<i>a sort of unwritten rule,</i>

12:48.680 --> 12:50.960
<i>certainly back</i>
<i>when I was first on Hydra,</i>

12:50.960 --> 12:53.320
<i>that if you saw someone</i>
<i>like Leonard at a table,</i>

12:53.320 --> 12:55.880
<i>you didn't assume</i>
<i>you could go and sit with him.</i>

12:55.880 --> 12:58.920
<i>They were there to be alone</i>
<i>and remain alone,</i>

12:58.920 --> 13:01.040
<i>and they were doing</i>
<i>their writing.</i>

13:21.560 --> 13:24.920
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>Leonard had the idea</i>
<i>that he needed to live</i>

13:24.920 --> 13:27.280
<i>part of the year in Montreal</i>

13:27.280 --> 13:30.880
<i>to see real life</i>
<i>and get inspired.</i>

13:30.880 --> 13:35.640
<i>Leonard was very vulnerable</i>

13:35.640 --> 13:38.360
<i>in his creativity.</i>

13:38.360 --> 13:42.640
COHEN:
<i>A large part of my life</i>
<i>was escaping. Whatever it was.</i>

13:42.640 --> 13:45.880
<i>Even if the situation</i>
<i>looked good, I had to escape,</i>

13:45.880 --> 13:48.240
<i>because it didn't</i>
<i>look good to me.</i>

13:48.240 --> 13:51.480
<i>So it was a selfish life,</i>
<i>and, uh...</i>

13:51.480 --> 13:53.560
<i>But, uh, it didn't</i>
<i>seem so at the time.</i>

13:53.560 --> 13:56.720
<i>It just seemed</i>
<i>a matter of survival.</i>

13:56.720 --> 13:58.720
<i>You know,</i>
<i>I guess the kids suffered</i>

13:58.720 --> 14:01.360
<i>and people</i>
<i>close to me suffered</i>

14:01.360 --> 14:03.520
<i>because</i>
<i>I was always leaving.</i>

14:03.520 --> 14:06.160
<i>I was always</i>
<i>trying to get away.</i>

14:08.160 --> 14:10.320
<i>I was very much encouraged</i>

14:10.320 --> 14:13.360
<i>by a friend of mine</i>
<i>by the name of Irving Layton.</i>

14:13.360 --> 14:15.880
<i>Influenced by his manner.</i>

14:15.880 --> 14:19.000
<i>After he'd ask me what</i>
<i>I'm doing, he'd always say,</i>

14:19.000 --> 14:22.000
<i>"Leonard, are you sure</i>
<i>you're doing the wrong thing?"</i>

14:22.000 --> 14:26.200
<i>And that really struck home.</i>
<i>That really sounded right.</i>

14:26.200 --> 14:28.360
And Cohen's concern
is my renunciation

14:28.360 --> 14:30.240
of the Canadian public.
Is this true,

14:30.240 --> 14:32.000
or do you have
some other concern, Mr. Cohen,

14:32.000 --> 14:34.560
that you'd like to get
off your chest right now?

14:34.560 --> 14:36.800
COHEN:
When I get up in the morning,

14:36.800 --> 14:39.040
my real concern
is to discover

14:39.040 --> 14:41.160
whether or not
I'm in a state of grace.

14:41.160 --> 14:45.080
BROOMFIELD:
<i>What do you think Leonard</i>
<i>loved so much about Irving?</i>

14:45.080 --> 14:46.920
LAYTON:
<i>He loved his intellect,</i>

14:46.920 --> 14:49.680
<i>he loved his imagination,</i>
<i>and he felt that</i>

14:49.680 --> 14:53.600
<i>Irving was the real thing</i>
<i>in terms of poetry.</i>

14:53.600 --> 14:56.600
<i>And the very first time</i>
<i>I saw Leonard,</i>

14:56.600 --> 14:59.160
Irving said, "I'm gonna
ask this man to come round,

14:59.160 --> 15:01.080
this boy-man to--"

15:01.080 --> 15:02.800
I think he was 19, 20--

15:02.800 --> 15:06.080
And I said, "Who is he?" And he
said, "He's the real thing."

15:06.080 --> 15:10.400
They each thought of each other
as the real thing.

15:10.400 --> 15:12.680
They also had a very strong
Jewish connection.

15:12.680 --> 15:15.240
That was a very strong thing
in Irving's life,

15:15.240 --> 15:17.600
a very strong thing
in Leonard's life.

15:17.600 --> 15:20.120
<i>Leonard was</i>
<i>an aristocratic Jew.</i>

15:20.120 --> 15:23.080
<i>Leonard came</i>
<i>from a wealthy family,</i>

15:23.080 --> 15:26.920
<i>very well-rooted</i>
<i>in Canadian culture.</i>

15:26.920 --> 15:28.960
<i>He came</i>
<i>from an educated family,</i>

15:28.960 --> 15:30.760
<i>highly educated family.</i>

15:30.760 --> 15:33.080
<i>I never knew</i>
<i>Leonard's father, of course,</i>

15:33.080 --> 15:35.120
<i>who died</i>
<i>when Leonard was young,</i>

15:35.120 --> 15:37.320
<i>but his mother, Masha,</i>

15:37.320 --> 15:42.040
<i>was as mad as a hatter.</i>

15:42.040 --> 15:43.440
Really mad.

15:43.440 --> 15:44.800
She had a thing about Irving--

15:44.800 --> 15:46.600
I wouldn't be
at all surprised...

15:46.600 --> 15:48.520
Leonard and I
would laugh about it.

15:48.520 --> 15:50.280
...whether
Irving and Masha ever

15:50.280 --> 15:51.920
actually went
to bed together.

15:51.920 --> 15:53.960
Irving went to bed
with everybody.

15:53.960 --> 15:55.440
Why not Leonard's mother?

15:55.440 --> 15:57.680
I mean...
And she was--

15:57.680 --> 16:00.920
She was
very attracted to Irving.

16:00.920 --> 16:05.720
And Irving might have--
She was very beautiful, but mad.

16:05.720 --> 16:10.680
I think really great writers
have to have mad,

16:10.680 --> 16:13.440
Oedipally mad mothers.

16:13.440 --> 16:16.480
And if that's the case,
then that's what he had.

16:16.480 --> 16:18.240
[CHUCKLES]

16:18.240 --> 16:20.720
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

16:20.720 --> 16:22.680
COHEN:
<i>I mean, I know that, uh,</i>

16:22.680 --> 16:26.280
<i>a lot of my love of music</i>
<i>comes from my mother,</i>

16:26.280 --> 16:28.800
<i>who, uh, had a lovely voice.</i>

16:28.800 --> 16:32.360
<i>She was Russian, and she</i>
<i>sang songs around the house.</i>

16:32.360 --> 16:33.720
<i>And I know that those--</i>

16:33.720 --> 16:35.600
<i>Those changes, those melodies,</i>

16:35.600 --> 16:36.880
<i>touched me very much,</i>

16:36.880 --> 16:38.880
<i>and that's certainly</i>
<i>an influence.</i>

16:38.880 --> 16:40.240
<i>She would sing with us.</i>

16:40.240 --> 16:41.400
<i>I'd take my guitar</i>

16:41.400 --> 16:43.040
<i>to a restaurant</i>
<i>with my friends,</i>

16:43.040 --> 16:44.440
<i>and my mother would come,</i>

16:44.440 --> 16:47.120
<i>and we'd often sing all night.</i>

16:47.120 --> 16:49.800
[♪♪♪]

16:51.160 --> 16:53.160
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

16:53.160 --> 16:55.440
[PLAYING MELODY]

17:06.320 --> 17:08.320
[LAUGHS, SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY]

17:10.360 --> 17:14.080
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION
AND PEOPLE LAUGHING]

17:14.080 --> 17:15.840
COHEN:
We're having fun!

17:17.280 --> 17:19.280
We're winning!
We're winning!

17:19.280 --> 17:21.040
We're winning
the internal battle!

17:21.040 --> 17:23.080
We're keeping a party going!

17:24.400 --> 17:26.720
We're keeping the party going.

17:26.720 --> 17:29.080
[PLAYING MELODY]
[GIGGLING]

17:30.480 --> 17:34.240
BACAL:
<i>He loved women.</i>
<i>No question about it.</i>

17:34.240 --> 17:39.160
<i>But he needed to be</i>
<i>his own person in his own way.</i>

17:39.160 --> 17:43.440
<i>So he could love women</i>
<i>from a distance...</i>

17:43.440 --> 17:46.400
<i>and love them when they</i>
<i>came through and make them--</i>

17:46.400 --> 17:50.520
<i>He could make women</i>
<i>feel good about themselves.</i>

17:50.520 --> 17:53.600
<i>And that's how he loved them.</i>

17:53.600 --> 17:55.800
<i>That's how he loved them.</i>

17:55.800 --> 17:58.840
<i>But he couldn't</i>
<i>give himself to them</i>

17:58.840 --> 18:02.600
<i>because he couldn't</i>
<i>give himself away.</i>

18:02.600 --> 18:06.240
[♪♪♪]

18:06.240 --> 18:09.360
IHLEN [IN ENGLISH]:
<i>I was not satisfied</i>
<i>with my life at all.</i>

18:09.360 --> 18:11.400
<i>I didn't know what to do.</i>

18:11.400 --> 18:14.320
<i>I was the only one</i>
<i>who didn't paint,</i>

18:14.320 --> 18:17.000
<i>write, sculpt.</i>

18:17.000 --> 18:19.800
<i>So everybody was artists.</i>

18:19.800 --> 18:23.720
<i>Lots of people came</i>
<i>off the boat to Hydra.</i>

18:25.080 --> 18:27.800
<i>Jacqueline Kennedy was there.</i>

18:27.800 --> 18:30.840
<i>Princess Margaret was there.</i>

18:30.840 --> 18:33.040
<i>So, what could I say?</i>

18:33.040 --> 18:36.080
<i>So finally, I would say,</i>

18:36.080 --> 18:38.520
<i>"I am an artist.</i>

18:38.520 --> 18:42.120
<i>Life is an art. I'm living."</i>

18:42.120 --> 18:44.480
<i>Not very original.</i>

18:44.480 --> 18:46.480
<i>I was looking at myself</i>
<i>and saying,</i>

18:46.480 --> 18:49.560
<i>"Oh, everything is wrong</i>
<i>with me," you know? So...</i>

18:50.520 --> 18:52.400
<i>it's a pity.</i>

18:54.200 --> 18:57.000
BROOMFIELD:
<i>Marianne had been</i>
<i>the one to support Leonard</i>

18:57.000 --> 18:59.680
<i>through the nightmare</i>
<i>of writing his last novel,</i>

18:59.680 --> 19:02.040
Beautiful Losers,
<i>on Hydra.</i>

19:03.360 --> 19:05.240
COHEN:
<i>I wrote</i>
<i>a lot of books there,</i>

19:05.240 --> 19:06.600
<i>and a lot of songs.</i>

19:06.600 --> 19:08.640
<i>I published a novel,</i> 
Beautiful Losers,

19:08.640 --> 19:12.320
<i>but I really couldn't</i>
<i>pay the rent.</i>

19:12.320 --> 19:14.320
LAYTON:
<i>Oh, yeah. He went quite crazy.</i>

19:14.320 --> 19:17.160
<i>I mean, you'd have to be crazy</i>
<i>to write</i> Beautiful Losers.

19:17.160 --> 19:21.800
<i>It's like-- It's like</i>
<i>a hallucinogenic madness.</i>

19:21.800 --> 19:25.800
<i>He used to stay out there</i>
<i>under that hot Greek sun,</i>

19:25.800 --> 19:27.880
<i>and Marianne would make him</i>

19:27.880 --> 19:30.320
<i>little baskets</i>
<i>of food and water</i>

19:30.320 --> 19:33.040
<i>and drop them over</i>
<i>to him, and--</i>

19:33.040 --> 19:36.320
<i>I mean, he wrote</i>
<i>that book in a fever.</i>

19:36.320 --> 19:38.800
<i>So he would never</i>
<i>have been able to do that</i>

19:38.800 --> 19:42.040
<i>anywhere else except</i>
<i>on that island.</i>

19:43.200 --> 19:45.560
VICK:
<i>Leonard had always used acid.</i>

19:45.560 --> 19:48.120
<i>It just gave you</i>
<i>that extra whoosh.</i>

19:48.120 --> 19:52.120
<i>It was never just like taking</i>
<i>it to get out of oneself.</i>

19:52.120 --> 19:55.880
<i>It was very much to do with</i>
<i>part of the spiritual search.</i>

19:55.880 --> 19:58.320
<i>It allowed him to go</i>
<i>into his madness, I think,</i>

19:58.320 --> 20:00.800
<i>which he probably couldn't</i>
<i>have done anywhere else.</i>

20:00.800 --> 20:03.280
<i>It allowed him to sit</i>
<i>in his terrace in the sun,</i>

20:03.280 --> 20:06.400
<i>take acid and speed.</i>

20:06.400 --> 20:09.320
Marianne, I mean,
she used to say, you know--

20:09.320 --> 20:10.760
She was there to sort of--

20:10.760 --> 20:12.800
Not pick up the pieces,
but just sort of

20:12.800 --> 20:18.160
to hold the man that had driven
himself to the<i> Beautiful Losers</i>

20:18.160 --> 20:21.200
and writing those extraordinary
pages day after day,

20:21.200 --> 20:24.000
in the sun,
lunatic that he was.

20:25.280 --> 20:27.320
COHEN:
<i>To find something</i>

20:27.320 --> 20:29.480
<i>that really addresses</i>
<i>my attention,</i>

20:29.480 --> 20:32.280
<i>I have to do a lot</i>
<i>of endless versions.</i>

20:32.280 --> 20:36.160
<i>Anything I can bring to it.</i>
<i>I try everything.</i>

20:36.160 --> 20:39.200
<i>Try to ignore it.</i>
<i>Try to address it.</i>

20:39.200 --> 20:41.720
<i>Try to get high.</i>

20:41.720 --> 20:45.560
<i>Try to get intoxicated.</i>
<i>Try to get sober, you know?</i>

20:45.560 --> 20:49.080
<i>All the versions of myself</i>
<i>that I can summon</i>

20:49.080 --> 20:53.720
<i>are summoned to participate</i>
<i>in this-- This workforce.</i>

20:53.720 --> 20:57.120
<i>So, uh, I try everything.</i>
<i>I'll do anything.</i>

20:58.640 --> 21:02.160
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>When</i> Beautiful Losers<i> came out,</i>

21:02.160 --> 21:04.440
<i>it was hardly read.</i>

21:04.440 --> 21:06.160
<i>I didn't understand any of it.</i>

21:06.160 --> 21:11.360
<i>Many intellectuals reading it</i>
<i>tried to understand it.</i>

21:11.360 --> 21:14.200
<i>But even they were left</i>
<i>bewildered.</i>

21:15.720 --> 21:17.880
But listen to what
some of the critics said

21:17.880 --> 21:19.040
about his latest book.

21:19.040 --> 21:22.040
[MAN READING ON-SCREEN TEXT]

21:34.360 --> 21:36.560
[♪♪♪]

21:38.120 --> 21:40.120
COHEN:
<i>After I finished</i> 
Beautiful Losers,

21:40.120 --> 21:42.960
<i>I thought that I would</i>
<i>go into music.</i>

21:42.960 --> 21:45.960
<i>I wasn't really making</i>
<i>a living as a writer.</i>

21:45.960 --> 21:49.240
<i>It was very hard</i>
<i>to support and feed the--</i>

21:49.240 --> 21:52.880
<i>The hungry mouths</i>
<i>that I was obliged to do.</i>

21:52.880 --> 21:54.480
<i>So I came back to America,</i>

21:54.480 --> 21:56.720
<i>and I didn't know</i>
<i>what had been happening</i>

21:56.720 --> 22:00.720
<i>in New York in, uh--</i>
<i>In folk music.</i>

22:00.720 --> 22:03.400
<i>I was completely unaware</i>
<i>of people like Phil Ochs</i>

22:03.400 --> 22:06.240
<i>or Dylan or Joan Baez.</i>

22:07.440 --> 22:09.200
COLLINS:
<i>Leonard found me,</i>

22:09.200 --> 22:11.640
<i>and he came</i>
<i>to my apartment,</i>

22:11.640 --> 22:14.600
<i>and he came in</i>
<i>and we had some coffee.</i>

22:14.600 --> 22:18.360
I said, "So?" And he said,
"Well, I can't sing.

22:18.360 --> 22:19.800
And I can't play the guitar.

22:19.800 --> 22:22.280
And I don't know
if this is a song."

22:22.280 --> 22:23.800
And then he played me:

22:23.800 --> 22:29.120
♪ Suzanne takes you down
To her place by the river ♪

22:29.120 --> 22:32.200
So I said,
"Leonard, that is a song!

22:32.200 --> 22:36.280
That's a song, and I have
to record that immediately."

22:36.280 --> 22:38.080
So he and I--

22:38.080 --> 22:41.840
Of course,
I recorded it right away.

22:41.840 --> 22:43.960
We became friends.

22:43.960 --> 22:47.080
<i>He was quite clear</i>
<i>that he never,</i>

22:47.080 --> 22:49.120
<i>ever wanted to sing in public.</i>

22:49.120 --> 22:51.320
<i>So about a year went by,</i>

22:51.320 --> 22:54.200
<i>and "Suzanne"</i>
<i>was a big song by then.</i>

22:54.200 --> 22:57.840
<i>And I was doing</i>
<i>a big fundraiser in New York,</i>

22:57.840 --> 23:00.280
<i>and I said,</i>
<i>"You have to come with me.</i>

23:00.280 --> 23:01.760
<i>I want to put you on-stage</i>

23:01.760 --> 23:04.000
<i>and I want you</i>
<i>to sing 'Suzanne.'</i>

23:04.000 --> 23:06.480
<i>Everybody is dying to</i>
<i>hear you sing this song."</i>

23:06.480 --> 23:09.160
<i>He said, "I can't sing.</i>
<i>I have a horrible voice."</i>

23:09.160 --> 23:11.240
<i>I said, "You don't have</i>
<i>a horrible voice."</i>

23:11.240 --> 23:14.080
<i>So he came out, and he stood</i>
<i>in the middle there</i>

23:14.080 --> 23:16.400
<i>and began singing the song.</i>

23:16.400 --> 23:18.520
<i>And I knew that he was</i>
<i>shaking like a leaf</i>

23:18.520 --> 23:22.640
<i>because I had seen him,</i>
<i>seen his hands on the guitar.</i>

23:22.640 --> 23:26.120
<i>In the middle of "Suzanne,"</i>
<i>he broke down and began to sob,</i>

23:26.120 --> 23:29.360
<i>heh, and walked off the stage.</i>

23:29.360 --> 23:32.360
He was dying of fear.

23:32.360 --> 23:37.200
He was having what we know
as a great, massive attack

23:37.200 --> 23:39.200
of-- Of stage fright.

23:40.640 --> 23:42.480
<i>So he came off the stage,</i>
<i>and I said,</i>

23:42.480 --> 23:44.560
<i>"Leonard,</i>
<i>this just will not do.</i>

23:44.560 --> 23:47.480
<i>You have to go back.</i>
<i>I'll go back with you,</i>

23:47.480 --> 23:49.360
<i>and we can</i>
<i>do the song together."</i>

23:49.360 --> 23:51.120
<i>He said-- Finally he said okay.</i>

23:51.120 --> 23:52.560
<i>So meantime, the whole audience</i>

23:52.560 --> 23:55.280
<i>is continuing to clap</i>
<i>and scream and carry on,</i>

23:55.280 --> 23:57.520
<i>'cause they'd gotten a taste.</i>

23:57.520 --> 24:01.000
<i>They could hear him sing.</i>
<i>They knew.</i>

24:01.000 --> 24:03.240
<i>So we went out together,</i>
<i>he finished the song,</i>

24:03.240 --> 24:07.160
<i>and by the time we finished,</i>
<i>he was a convert.</i>

24:07.160 --> 24:12.120
<i>Total convert to</i>
<i>his own magical impression.</i>

24:12.120 --> 24:15.840
I would like to introduce
to you Mr. Leonard Cohen.

24:15.840 --> 24:17.400
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

24:18.760 --> 24:22.520
♪ Suzanne takes you down ♪

24:22.520 --> 24:26.120
♪ To her place near the river ♪

24:26.120 --> 24:29.600
♪ You can hear
The boats go by ♪

24:29.600 --> 24:33.120
♪ You can spend the night
Beside her ♪

24:33.120 --> 24:36.560
♪ And you know
She's half crazy ♪

24:36.560 --> 24:40.040
♪ But that's why
You want to be there ♪

24:40.040 --> 24:43.600
♪ And she feeds you
Tea and oranges ♪

24:43.600 --> 24:46.560
♪ That come all the way
From China... ♪

24:46.560 --> 24:49.200
COLLINS:
<i>It was one of</i>
<i>the most important moments</i>

24:49.200 --> 24:52.480
<i>of his life and mine.</i>

24:52.480 --> 24:54.640
<i>And of course,</i>
<i>then he was off to the races.</i>

24:54.640 --> 24:59.040
<i>Columbia signed him up</i>
<i>and was his label forever.</i>

25:00.920 --> 25:04.360
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>He often had</i>
<i>to cross the "great dam."</i>

25:04.360 --> 25:08.680
<i>Both to search</i>
<i>inspiration and...</i>

25:08.680 --> 25:11.400
[IN ENGLISH]
<i>become a little</i>
<i>more miserable again, heh.</i>

25:11.400 --> 25:14.680
[IN NORWEGIAN]
<i>We couldn't afford</i>
<i>all three of us to travel.</i>

25:14.680 --> 25:18.600
<i>So I was often alone on Hydra.</i>

25:18.600 --> 25:20.200
<i>And I got to the point</i>

25:20.200 --> 25:22.720
<i>where I didn't want</i>
<i>to be alone anymore.</i>

25:22.720 --> 25:24.680
<i>I was sad.</i>

25:26.040 --> 25:28.840
<i>It wasn't long</i>
<i>before I received a telegram.</i>

25:29.960 --> 25:32.160
[IN ENGLISH]
<i>"Have house.</i>

25:32.160 --> 25:36.080
<i>All I need</i>
<i>is my woman and her son.</i>

25:36.080 --> 25:37.720
<i>Love, Leonard."</i>

25:38.760 --> 25:40.640
[IN NORWEGIAN]
<i>And that was it.</i>

25:40.640 --> 25:43.720
<i>I went to him.</i>

25:43.720 --> 25:46.480
COHEN:
<i>I remember her</i>
<i>arriving at the airport.</i>

25:46.480 --> 25:50.240
<i>She had two heavy valises</i>
<i>in each hand.</i>

25:50.240 --> 25:51.760
<i>She couldn't wave to me</i>

25:51.760 --> 25:55.240
<i>because she couldn't</i>
<i>lift the suitcases up,</i>

25:55.240 --> 25:57.560
<i>but she didn't want</i>
<i>to drop them-- She was moving.</i>

25:57.560 --> 26:00.760
<i>So she waved to me</i>
<i>with her foot.</i>

26:00.760 --> 26:02.640
<i>I remember that</i>
<i>very, very clearly.</i>

26:02.640 --> 26:04.360
<i>[CHUCKLES]</i>

26:04.360 --> 26:07.200
LAYTON:
<i>Yeah, boy,</i>
<i>that was a mistake.</i>

26:07.200 --> 26:10.840
You know, and said famously--
You know, the famous thing.

26:10.840 --> 26:13.400
"I want my woman."
I mean, that was Leonard, yeah?

26:13.400 --> 26:17.480
"I want my woman and my child
to come to Montreal."

26:17.480 --> 26:19.760
And that was
this wonderful thing.

26:19.760 --> 26:22.280
And of course, the minute
he said it, he didn't--

26:22.280 --> 26:24.960
He wouldn't have--
He didn't need it anymore.

26:24.960 --> 26:27.040
He needed to say it, but--

26:27.040 --> 26:31.120
And Marianne, who was
deeply in love with him,

26:31.120 --> 26:33.480
did come
and brought Little Axel.

26:33.480 --> 26:35.880
We always used to call him
"Little Axel."

26:35.880 --> 26:38.240
And, um, it was a disaster.

26:38.240 --> 26:41.440
It was very unhappy.
A very unhappy time.

26:41.440 --> 26:44.640
<i>Axel would come</i>
<i>and stay with us.</i>

26:44.640 --> 26:48.840
<i>He used to take a pencil</i>
<i>and pencil his name</i>

26:48.840 --> 26:52.800
<i>over every wall</i>
<i>in our apartment.</i>

26:52.800 --> 26:55.240
<i>He'd write,</i>
<i>"Axel, Axel, Axel."</i>

26:55.240 --> 26:58.840
<i>That was a very unhappy time.</i>

26:58.840 --> 27:03.040
Poets do not make
great husbands, do they?

27:03.040 --> 27:05.280
Do you know of a poet
who's ever made

27:05.280 --> 27:09.000
an absolutely splendid husband?

27:09.000 --> 27:10.920
Or a filmmaker?

27:10.920 --> 27:13.440
Or an artist?

27:13.440 --> 27:15.720
No. You can't own them.

27:15.720 --> 27:18.800
You can't even own
a bit of them.

27:18.800 --> 27:23.160
They're--
They're just elusive creatures

27:23.160 --> 27:27.800
who are married to their...
To their muse.

27:27.800 --> 27:31.600
That sounds so pretentious
to say that, but it's true.

27:32.640 --> 27:37.160
But the irony is,
a man like that

27:37.160 --> 27:42.280
is a man who every woman
wants to have...

27:42.280 --> 27:44.320
and can't have.

27:46.160 --> 27:49.960
COLLINS:
<i>Marianne came up to me,</i>
<i>and she said,</i>

27:49.960 --> 27:53.280
<i>"We were very happy</i>
<i>living in Hydra.</i>

27:53.280 --> 27:55.800
<i>And we were walking</i>
<i>on the beach</i>

27:55.800 --> 27:57.880
<i>and we were swimming</i>
<i>in the nude</i>

27:57.880 --> 28:01.240
<i>and drinking a lot of retsina,</i>
<i>and we were very happy.</i>

28:01.240 --> 28:03.640
<i>And then one day,</i>
<i>he came to me and he said,</i>

28:03.640 --> 28:06.520
<i>'Marianne,</i>
<i>I'm going to New York</i>

28:06.520 --> 28:09.440
<i>to play my songs</i>
<i>for Judy Collins.'</i>

28:09.440 --> 28:11.480
<i>And you recorded</i>
<i>all of his songs.</i>

28:11.480 --> 28:16.600
<i>And I just wanted to tell you</i>
<i>that you ruined my life."</i>

28:16.600 --> 28:20.000
<i>Certainly their dream life</i>
<i>in Hydra</i>

28:20.000 --> 28:22.960
<i>had a big interruption,</i>
<i>which was that</i>

28:22.960 --> 28:26.480
<i>Leonard discovered himself</i>
<i>as a singer.</i>

28:26.480 --> 28:29.280
[♪♪♪]

28:31.920 --> 28:36.480
BROOMFIELD:
<i>I took this picture of Marianne</i>
<i>in the autumn of 1968,</i>

28:36.480 --> 28:40.000
<i>when she came to the U.K.</i>
<i>and contacted me.</i>

28:40.000 --> 28:43.200
<i>She had come to bring</i>
<i>Little Axel to boarding school</i>

28:43.200 --> 28:45.120
<i>and needed a lift.</i>

28:47.040 --> 28:48.600
<i>We drove down to Suffolk,</i>

28:48.600 --> 28:50.960
<i>to Summerhill,</i>
<i>the A.S. Neill school,</i>

28:50.960 --> 28:53.640
<i>where children didn't</i>
<i>have to attend class</i>

28:53.640 --> 28:55.520
<i>if they didn't want to.</i>

28:58.280 --> 29:00.320
<i>Axel was 8, and I remember</i>

29:00.320 --> 29:03.080
<i>how upset he was</i>
<i>when we drove away.</i>

29:05.280 --> 29:08.520
<i>Axel would write to Marianne</i>
<i>nearly every day.</i>

29:18.160 --> 29:20.320
<i>Marianne was in tears too,</i>

29:20.320 --> 29:22.600
<i>but believed it was</i>
<i>the best thing for him</i>

29:22.600 --> 29:24.840
<i>because she was</i>
<i>always traveling.</i>

29:26.240 --> 29:28.360
<i>Marianne came</i>
<i>and stayed for a while</i>

29:28.360 --> 29:31.400
<i>in my less-than-chic squat</i>
<i>in Kentish Town,</i>

29:31.400 --> 29:34.120
<i>where she took this photo.</i>

29:34.120 --> 29:37.320
<i>She introduced me to the world</i>
<i>of protest movements</i>

29:37.320 --> 29:41.680
<i>and artists using their art</i>
<i>to achieve incredible things.</i>

29:41.680 --> 29:44.280
<i>She was close</i>
<i>to Julie Felix, the singer,</i>

29:44.280 --> 29:46.400
<i>an old friend</i>
<i>of hers and Leonard's,</i>

29:46.400 --> 29:49.000
<i>and working with Julie</i>
<i>as her muse,</i>

29:49.000 --> 29:51.320
<i>encouraging her</i>
<i>to write her own songs</i>

29:51.320 --> 29:54.120
<i>for the very first time.</i>

29:54.120 --> 29:56.680
<i>Julie had originally</i>
<i>met Leonard on Hydra,</i>

29:56.680 --> 29:59.920
<i>before either of them</i>
<i>were singers.</i>

29:59.920 --> 30:02.760
I'm very happy and proud
to have him here on the show

30:02.760 --> 30:05.000
and introduce him
to the English public.

30:05.000 --> 30:07.800
Here is the writer,
the poet, the songwriter.

30:07.800 --> 30:10.720
He's a friend, but he says
he's a stranger in this song.

30:10.720 --> 30:14.040
Ladies and gentleman,
Leonard Cohen.

30:14.040 --> 30:16.000
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

30:20.200 --> 30:23.640
♪ It's true that
All the men you knew ♪

30:23.640 --> 30:27.680
♪ Were dealers who said they
Were through with dealing ♪

30:27.680 --> 30:32.280
♪ Every time
You gave them shelter ♪

30:32.280 --> 30:36.440
♪ I know that kind of man
It's hard to hold the hand ♪

30:36.440 --> 30:39.800
♪ Of anyone who's reaching
For the sky... ♪

30:39.800 --> 30:41.600
FELIX:
<i>Leonard was always searching.</i>

30:41.600 --> 30:45.280
<i>And this feeling of</i>
<i>never belonging anywhere,</i>

30:45.280 --> 30:48.440
<i>and even in a relationship,</i>
<i>you know, eventually--</i>

30:48.440 --> 30:50.680
<i>With Marianne, I think</i>
<i>that was the longest.</i>

30:50.680 --> 30:55.160
<i>But after that, he went from</i>
<i>relationship to relationship.</i>

30:55.160 --> 30:56.560
<i>And at the end of the song,</i>

30:56.560 --> 30:59.920
<i>there was</i>
<i>just a tear in his eye.</i>

30:59.920 --> 31:02.960
<i>He was an emotional man.</i>

31:02.960 --> 31:06.400
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

31:06.400 --> 31:10.040
<i>Well, at that time they were</i>
<i>already having a few problems.</i>

31:10.040 --> 31:12.880
Marianne and I hung out
together for quite a while,

31:12.880 --> 31:14.320
and we became very close.

31:14.320 --> 31:17.680
And, um, we went on
a couple of trips together,

31:17.680 --> 31:21.560
and she was the muse and said,
you know, "Why don't you write?"

31:21.560 --> 31:23.960
And the first song I wrote
was "Windy Morning,"

31:23.960 --> 31:28.600
which is a song that
she kind of guided me through.

31:28.600 --> 31:31.000
BROOMFIELD:
She was a great muse,
wasn't she?

31:31.000 --> 31:33.200
Absolutely. Absolutely.

31:33.200 --> 31:37.120
And, uh-- And I think Leonard
honored that, you know?

31:37.120 --> 31:41.600
He said that she was,
you know, when... When...

31:41.600 --> 31:44.240
When he was speaking of her.

31:44.240 --> 31:46.200
BROOMFIELD:
She was so encouraging.

31:46.200 --> 31:49.240
Yeah. She was so nurturing,
you know.

31:49.240 --> 31:51.920
It's-- It's, uh...

31:51.920 --> 31:57.120
Yeah, it's that, you know,
the... woman power,

31:57.120 --> 32:01.200
the ability
to nurture and love and--

32:01.200 --> 32:04.600
And, uh, encourage, you know?

32:04.600 --> 32:06.720
It's something the world needs.

32:06.720 --> 32:08.120
That's why I think it's good

32:08.120 --> 32:10.320
that we're getting
to women's time finally,

32:10.320 --> 32:12.920
with all the "Time's Up."

32:12.920 --> 32:16.840
And Leonard was a great, uh...

32:16.840 --> 32:20.200
He was a feminist, you know?
He really, uh...

32:20.200 --> 32:23.320
He said to me once, 'cause
I was talking about something--

32:23.320 --> 32:25.720
He said, "I can't wait
till women take over."

32:25.720 --> 32:28.920
So that was kind of nice
to hear from him.

32:28.920 --> 32:31.720
[♪♪♪]

32:40.280 --> 32:44.040
SIMON:
<i>Leonard's imagery</i>
<i>came from the poets,</i>

32:44.040 --> 32:48.640
<i>from Shakespeare,</i>
<i>from Keats, from Marlowe.</i>

32:48.640 --> 32:51.840
So I found certain lines
in his guitar playing

32:51.840 --> 32:54.200
that I could enrich.

32:54.200 --> 32:57.080
And I decided not to do it
with instruments

32:57.080 --> 33:00.400
but to do it
with female voices,

33:00.400 --> 33:02.200
since so much of his writing

33:02.200 --> 33:06.160
was about his relationships
with women.

33:06.160 --> 33:09.520
There was a very female presence
in all of his songs,

33:09.520 --> 33:11.960
even though he was a man.

33:11.960 --> 33:13.760
So my girlfriend at the time

33:13.760 --> 33:16.280
had a very nice
pure, soprano voice,

33:16.280 --> 33:19.520
and so I started,
you know, fooling around,

33:19.520 --> 33:22.200
asking her,
"Sing this, sing this,"

33:22.200 --> 33:24.240
over Leonard's song.
"What do you think?"

33:24.240 --> 33:27.040
And, uh, some of it
sounded really great.

33:27.040 --> 33:29.240
BROOMFIELD:
You can't sort of
imitate it slightly?

33:29.240 --> 33:30.440
[LAUGHS]

33:30.440 --> 33:32.240
I'm not a singer,
and I'm not a girl.

33:32.240 --> 33:35.240
She was singing,
♪ So long, Marianne ♪

33:35.240 --> 33:37.080
She added that little "--anne"
on the top.

33:37.080 --> 33:39.400
♪ It's time that
We began to laugh ♪

33:39.400 --> 33:43.000
♪ And cry
And laugh and cry ♪

33:43.000 --> 33:44.680
♪ About it all again ♪

33:44.680 --> 33:47.240
So she sort of aped
what he was doing,

33:47.240 --> 33:49.600
but it gave it
a little harder...

33:49.600 --> 33:52.120
Put a little harder edge
on it, you know?

33:52.120 --> 33:54.760
♪ So long, Marianne ♪

33:54.760 --> 33:57.600
♪ It's time that we began ♪

33:57.600 --> 34:00.800
♪ To laugh and cry ♪
♪ To laugh and cry ♪

34:00.800 --> 34:06.720
♪ And cry and laugh
About it all again ♪

34:06.720 --> 34:09.600
♪ So long, Marianne ♪

34:09.600 --> 34:16.240
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>There are aspects of our life</i>
<i>in that song.</i>

34:16.240 --> 34:19.960
<i>And when you mention the lyric,</i>

34:19.960 --> 34:24.320
[IN ENGLISH]
<i>"Fine spider-web fastening</i>
<i>my ankle to a stone,"</i>

34:24.320 --> 34:29.320
[IN NORWEGIAN]
<i>it reminds me of something</i>
<i>that he told me.</i>

34:29.320 --> 34:33.280
<i>It was</i>
<i>his record release party.</i>

34:33.280 --> 34:36.080
<i>Leonard was</i>
<i>the center of attention.</i>

34:36.080 --> 34:40.280
<i>So he went to the top floor</i>
<i>of the apartment,</i>

34:40.280 --> 34:43.120
<i>on the roof terrace.</i>

34:43.120 --> 34:47.200
<i>He just had</i>
<i>to get away from it all,</i>

34:47.200 --> 34:50.160
<i>and he told me very seriously</i>

34:50.160 --> 34:52.760
[IN ENGLISH]
<i>if this was part of the game,</i>

34:52.760 --> 34:55.480
<i>he didn't know</i>
<i>how long he would last.</i>

34:57.680 --> 34:59.960
The very first time
I met Leonard Cohen,

34:59.960 --> 35:01.240
he opened the door,

35:01.240 --> 35:04.520
and he's absolutely naked
as a jaybird.

35:04.520 --> 35:08.560
Right? So me, coming out of
where I come out of, I go,

35:08.560 --> 35:12.360
"This is pretty damn weird,"
you know? "This is..."

35:12.360 --> 35:15.720
Later, of course, throughout
the time I spent with Leonard,

35:15.720 --> 35:19.040
the years
that we worked together,

35:19.040 --> 35:21.680
uh, when I look back
on all that,

35:21.680 --> 35:25.200
and if I'd have been
evolved enough

35:25.200 --> 35:29.160
at that moment, it wouldn't
have been weird to me at all.

35:29.160 --> 35:31.080
<i>All the time I knew Leonard,</i>

35:31.080 --> 35:35.440
<i>he was very, very conscious</i>
<i>of his body.</i>

35:35.440 --> 35:38.120
<i>Leonard used to say</i>
<i>that when we're on tour,</i>

35:38.120 --> 35:40.720
<i>and you get--</i>
<i>We're at the hotel,</i>

35:40.720 --> 35:42.640
<i>take all your clothes off.</i>

35:42.640 --> 35:45.200
<i>You're going</i>
<i>to be passing by</i>

35:45.200 --> 35:48.640
<i>these things</i>
<i>called mirrors, right?</i>

35:48.640 --> 35:51.080
And when you pass by a mirror,

35:51.080 --> 35:53.360
you're gonna notice
that little...

35:53.360 --> 35:55.960
"Hey, I need to be doing
a few more sit-ups."

35:57.720 --> 36:01.160
<i>Leonard swam,</i>
<i>like, all the time.</i>

36:01.160 --> 36:03.800
<i>Any hotel we were in,</i>
<i>you would find--</i>

36:03.800 --> 36:07.400
<i>If they had-- If they had</i>
<i>a pool, he was in it.</i>

36:07.400 --> 36:09.360
<i>And he would get up</i>
<i>early in the morning</i>

36:09.360 --> 36:11.440
<i>so he didn't</i>
<i>have to run into anybody.</i>

36:11.440 --> 36:13.680
<i>He'd be down there</i>
<i>at 5:00 in the morning,</i>

36:13.680 --> 36:15.240
<i>and he'd be doing laps.</i>

36:15.240 --> 36:17.760
<i>And if they would</i>
<i>let him swim nude,</i>

36:17.760 --> 36:19.640
<i>he would swim nude.</i>

36:19.640 --> 36:22.760
<i>I don't know why.</i>
<i>That was just him.</i>

36:24.280 --> 36:26.440
BROOMFIELD:
<i>Didn't you write</i>
<i>a song with him?</i>

36:26.440 --> 36:30.000
CORNELIUS:
<i>I did. Yeah, I wrote</i>
<i>"Chelsea Hotel" with him.</i>

36:30.000 --> 36:32.680
<i>We boarded an airplane</i>
<i>in LaGuardia,</i>

36:32.680 --> 36:36.960
<i>and me and Leonard sat there</i>
<i>and worked on this song.</i>

36:38.400 --> 36:41.480
<i>I had no idea</i>
<i>who he was talking to</i>

36:41.480 --> 36:43.840
<i>in his writing at the time.</i>

36:43.840 --> 36:48.160
<i>It came out later</i>
<i>that it was about Janis Joplin.</i>

36:48.160 --> 36:50.680
And, you know, it's like,

36:50.680 --> 36:53.360
"Remember you well
at the Chelsea Hotel,

36:53.360 --> 36:56.000
uh, talking so brave
and so sweet,

36:56.000 --> 36:57.680
giving me head
on the unmade bed

36:57.680 --> 36:59.920
while the limousines
wait in the street."

36:59.920 --> 37:01.400
That's all still there.

37:01.400 --> 37:03.480
Nobody knows that
the second verse was,

37:03.480 --> 37:06.280
"I remember you well
at the Chelsea Hotel

37:06.280 --> 37:08.920
in the winter of 1967.

37:08.920 --> 37:12.320
My friends of that year,
they were all turning queer,

37:12.320 --> 37:15.480
and me, I was just
getting even."

37:15.480 --> 37:18.800
♪ I remember you well ♪

37:18.800 --> 37:22.200
♪ In the Chelsea Hotel ♪

37:22.200 --> 37:25.400
♪ You were talkin' so brave ♪

37:25.400 --> 37:27.600
♪ And so sweet ♪

37:30.480 --> 37:32.720
♪ Giving me head ♪

37:32.720 --> 37:35.720
♪ On an unmade bed ♪

37:35.720 --> 37:38.400
♪ While the limousines ♪

37:38.400 --> 37:40.920
♪ Wait in the street... ♪

37:43.640 --> 37:48.120
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>I moved to New York</i>
<i>to be with Leonard.</i>

37:48.120 --> 37:52.800
<i>He was living between our home</i>
<i>and the Chelsea Hotel.</i>

37:54.280 --> 37:56.440
<i>He took me to a concert</i>

37:56.440 --> 38:00.400
<i>to see</i>
<i>the fantastic Janis Joplin.</i>

38:00.400 --> 38:03.600
[♪♪♪]

38:09.200 --> 38:11.640
<i>I didn't join them</i>
<i>after the concert.</i>

38:11.640 --> 38:15.160
<i>Leonard was always protective</i>
<i>of that life.</i>

38:15.160 --> 38:17.400
<i>I was grateful for that.</i>

38:20.240 --> 38:23.080
<i>I didn't really have</i>
<i>anything to do there.</i>

38:26.560 --> 38:30.840
<i>Whatever he did</i>
<i>while he was in New York,</i>

38:30.840 --> 38:34.760
<i>whether I was there or Hydra...</i>

38:34.760 --> 38:36.840
<i>he never shared that with me.</i>

38:36.840 --> 38:40.040
<i>It was a very hard time.</i>

38:42.760 --> 38:44.400
MOLLESTAD:
<i>At that time,</i>

38:44.400 --> 38:47.720
<i>Leonard had some experiences</i>
<i>with Janis Joplin,</i>

38:47.720 --> 38:49.760
<i>all these things.</i>

38:49.760 --> 38:53.480
And Marianne
was living separately

38:53.480 --> 38:56.320
in her apartment
with Little Axel.

38:56.320 --> 39:01.920
That must've been, uh...
very strange.

39:01.920 --> 39:04.640
But she was still the muse.

39:04.640 --> 39:07.360
And the interesting thing
is that

39:07.360 --> 39:11.920
she has read for me
the telegrams...

39:11.920 --> 39:13.880
from Leonard.

39:13.880 --> 39:16.600
First telegrams to...

39:17.640 --> 39:19.840
"Marianne Cohen."

39:21.000 --> 39:24.400
It was just like
they had been married.

39:24.400 --> 39:27.480
Telegrams going to Hydra
and then to London

39:27.480 --> 39:30.200
and then to New York,

39:30.200 --> 39:31.720
first it's in the period

39:31.720 --> 39:34.120
when they are together
as a couple.

39:34.120 --> 39:36.680
But the beautiful thing is,

39:36.680 --> 39:38.560
when they're not
a couple anymore,

39:38.560 --> 39:40.640
he's still sending money,

39:40.640 --> 39:46.840
he's still asking
how Axel is doing.

39:46.840 --> 39:49.760
And so he continues to send

39:49.760 --> 39:53.520
his, uh, small...

39:53.520 --> 39:55.360
uh...

39:55.360 --> 39:57.720
love messages,

39:57.720 --> 39:59.840
even if they're not together.

39:59.840 --> 40:01.840
[♪♪♪]

40:01.840 --> 40:05.320
CORNELIUS:
<i>Leonard said he was</i>
<i>suffering from depression</i>

40:05.320 --> 40:08.360
<i>that he fought</i>
<i>for so many years.</i>

40:10.080 --> 40:13.080
So Leonard decided,
he thought, well, it'd be, uh,

40:13.080 --> 40:16.840
a nice thing for us
to do is that

40:16.840 --> 40:19.240
we blow in--
Say we blew into London

40:19.240 --> 40:20.920
to play the Royal Albert Hall.

40:20.920 --> 40:23.000
"Well, uh, we got
three or four days here.

40:23.000 --> 40:25.200
Why don't we, one evening,
go out and play

40:25.200 --> 40:28.200
at a mental institution,"
right?

40:28.200 --> 40:30.520
Okay, so of course
that went over

40:30.520 --> 40:33.080
like a fart in a diver's helmet
with me,

40:33.080 --> 40:37.640
'cause I wasn't about
to go out to any...

40:37.640 --> 40:41.320
I was not going. No way.

40:41.320 --> 40:45.680
He said, you know,
"Just go one time."

40:45.680 --> 40:47.920
He said, "If you go one time

40:47.920 --> 40:50.760
and don't want to play
any more of these,

40:50.760 --> 40:53.120
then you don't have
to do it," right?

40:53.120 --> 40:55.520
So I said okay. So I went.

40:55.520 --> 40:57.680
Well, I'm gonna tell you this.

40:57.680 --> 41:01.760
By the time
that night was over...

41:01.760 --> 41:05.400
you couldn't drive me
away from that idea.

41:05.400 --> 41:08.400
<i>And we ended up</i>
<i>playing a lot of them.</i>

41:08.400 --> 41:11.320
<i>He had a grandfather</i>
<i>or something like that</i>

41:11.320 --> 41:16.080
<i>that I think died in</i>
<i>one of those institutions.</i>

41:16.080 --> 41:19.760
COHEN:
<i>There are a number of reasons</i>
<i>why I played mental hospitals.</i>

41:19.760 --> 41:25.400
<i>When you play for somebody</i>
<i>who has really been defeated--</i>

41:25.400 --> 41:27.040
<i>And it was my feeling</i>

41:27.040 --> 41:29.400
<i>that the elements</i>
<i>of this defeat corresponded</i>

41:29.400 --> 41:33.240
<i>with certain elements</i>
<i>that produced my songs</i>

41:33.240 --> 41:36.320
<i>and that there would be</i>
<i>an empathy.</i>

41:36.320 --> 41:38.560
<i>I mean, I feel</i>
<i>that I also have an empathy</i>

41:38.560 --> 41:41.440
<i>with this experience.</i>

41:41.440 --> 41:45.240
<i>When I told them I was</i>
<i>coming out here, they said,</i>

41:45.240 --> 41:47.800
<i>"They're a tough bunch</i>
<i>of young nuts."</i>

41:47.800 --> 41:50.080
<i>[AUDIENCE CHUCKLING]</i>

41:51.480 --> 41:53.880
<i>This song is about a girl</i>
<i>I used to live with.</i>

41:53.880 --> 41:58.560
<i>I lived with her</i>
<i>for about, uh, eight years.</i>

41:58.560 --> 42:01.160
<i>Her name was Marianne.</i>

42:01.160 --> 42:04.560
<i>And, uh, I used</i>
<i>to live with her</i>

42:04.560 --> 42:07.360
<i>you know,</i>
<i>for six months of the year,</i>

42:07.360 --> 42:09.360
<i>and then the other six months</i>
<i>of the year</i>

42:09.360 --> 42:11.480
<i>I would spend</i>
<i>with someone else.</i>

42:11.480 --> 42:15.440
<i>Then I found myself living with</i>
<i>her four months of the year.</i>

42:15.440 --> 42:17.240
<i>Then two months of the year.</i>

42:17.240 --> 42:20.520
<i>Then by the eighth year,</i>
<i>I was living with her</i>

42:20.520 --> 42:23.360
<i>a couple of weeks of the year.</i>

42:23.360 --> 42:24.760
<i>But I thought it was time</i>

42:24.760 --> 42:28.360
<i>to write</i>
<i>this particular song for her.</i>

42:28.360 --> 42:31.120
<i>I still live with her</i>
<i>a couple of days of the year.</i>

42:31.120 --> 42:33.000
<i>[AUDIENCE LAUGHS]</i>

42:34.200 --> 42:37.720
<i>♪ For I love you</i>
<i>In the morning ♪</i>

42:37.720 --> 42:41.280
<i>♪ Our kisses deep and warm ♪</i>

42:41.280 --> 42:44.360
<i>♪ Your hair upon the pillow ♪</i>

42:44.360 --> 42:48.600
<i>♪ Like a sleepy</i>
<i>Golden storm... ♪</i>

42:52.280 --> 42:56.960
CORNELIUS:
<i>That was a moment in my life</i>
<i>that I would never forget.</i>

42:58.160 --> 43:00.800
<i>And this guy, he stands up</i>

43:00.800 --> 43:03.360
<i>and starts screaming,</i>
<i>you know,</i>

43:03.360 --> 43:06.320
<i>"Hey, shut it down.</i>
<i>Stop. Shut it."</i>

43:06.320 --> 43:08.680
Well, we, you know,

43:08.680 --> 43:13.000
being musicians and have
played a million shows,

43:13.000 --> 43:14.760
we steam right on, right?

43:14.760 --> 43:16.720
We're not gonna let that--
Well, no.

43:16.720 --> 43:21.840
This guy shut it down.
He shut it down.

43:21.840 --> 43:24.360
And then,
Leonard finally said,

43:24.360 --> 43:28.440
"Okay, you talk then," right?
So this guy said, "Look."

43:28.440 --> 43:32.240
He said, "You come in here,

43:32.240 --> 43:35.800
and you got all these shiny
guitars and you got all--

43:35.800 --> 43:38.000
And you got
the pretty girls there

43:38.000 --> 43:41.000
singing background and stuff,
and everything like--"

43:41.000 --> 43:43.880
He said, "I wanna know,
what do you think about me?

43:43.880 --> 43:46.560
That's what I wanna know about.

43:46.560 --> 43:50.400
I wanna know
what you think about me."

43:52.560 --> 43:56.200
You could hear
a pin drop in that place.

43:56.200 --> 43:59.240
And Leonard just walked
past me and Charlie,

43:59.240 --> 44:02.520
walked down the stairs,
walked right out in the crowd

44:02.520 --> 44:05.600
and just hugged him like
you wouldn't have believed.

44:05.600 --> 44:08.800
He almost broke his ribs,
he hugged him that hard.

44:08.800 --> 44:12.360
[♪♪♪]

44:12.360 --> 44:14.880
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>I wanted to put him in a cage,</i>

44:14.880 --> 44:19.200
<i>lock him up</i>
<i>and swallow the key.</i>

44:19.200 --> 44:23.200
<i>He was always</i>
<i>sought after by everyone.</i>

44:23.200 --> 44:27.480
<i>People loved how entertaining</i>
<i>and compassionate he was.</i>

44:27.480 --> 44:29.400
<i>That's the way it goes</i>

44:29.400 --> 44:34.480
<i>when you choose those</i>
<i>strong, dark, handsome men.</i>

44:34.480 --> 44:37.240
<i>All the girls</i>
<i>were panting for him.</i>

44:38.520 --> 44:43.280
<i>It hurt me so much.</i>
<i>It destroyed me.</i>

44:43.280 --> 44:48.040
<i>I was on the verge of killing</i>
<i>myself because of it.</i>

44:49.680 --> 44:51.600
<i>I wanted to die.</i>

44:55.560 --> 44:58.160
I came to see you because it's--
You don't sing anymore?

44:58.160 --> 44:59.880
COHEN: Pardon?
[SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY]

44:59.880 --> 45:02.160
Well, we go to Geneva.
No, I mean now.

45:02.160 --> 45:04.640
Now? No. Why are you--?
No, tonight.

45:04.640 --> 45:07.560
Would you like to listen?
Yes. Yeah.

45:08.920 --> 45:11.000
Um, I don't
have any plans, but--

45:11.000 --> 45:13.440
You don't have any place?
No, I don't have any place.

45:13.440 --> 45:17.760
Do you have somewhere for me?
Yes. A lot.

45:17.760 --> 45:19.560
Okay.

45:19.560 --> 45:21.560
[CHUCKLES]

45:21.560 --> 45:24.080
It's hard to come on to a girl
in front of the camera.

45:24.080 --> 45:26.400
What?

45:26.400 --> 45:29.080
COHEN:
<i>I was obsessed by, uh,</i>

45:29.080 --> 45:32.440
<i>gaining women's favors</i>
<i>at a certain point in my life.</i>

45:32.440 --> 45:37.360
<i>And, um, way beyond</i>
<i>any, uh, reasonable,</i>

45:37.360 --> 45:40.240
<i>uh, activity.</i>

45:40.240 --> 45:42.520
<i>It became the most important</i>
<i>thing in my life,</i>

45:42.520 --> 45:45.760
<i>and it led me into</i>
<i>very obsessive, uh, behavior</i>

45:45.760 --> 45:47.680
<i>and some very</i>
<i>interesting things,</i>

45:47.680 --> 45:50.920
<i>and probably most of the things</i>
<i>I learned about myself</i>

45:50.920 --> 45:53.120
<i>and about other people</i>

45:53.120 --> 45:56.160
<i>were gained from</i>
<i>this period of obsessive--</i>

45:56.160 --> 45:58.920
<i>This blue movie</i>
<i>that I threw myself into.</i>

45:58.920 --> 46:02.200
<i>But we know that blue movies</i>
<i>are not romantic.</i>

46:02.200 --> 46:04.800
<i>[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]</i>

46:07.280 --> 46:11.240
DONOVAN:
<i>It was a show.</i>
<i>It was more women than men.</i>

46:11.240 --> 46:13.040
<i>It was like,</i>
<i>you'd look out there,</i>

46:13.040 --> 46:14.400
<i>and there were some couples,</i>

46:14.400 --> 46:17.320
<i>and it was mostly just women.</i>

46:17.320 --> 46:19.400
<i>They've read his poetry, right?</i>

46:19.400 --> 46:21.600
<i>And then they see him</i>
<i>sing these songs,</i>

46:21.600 --> 46:23.600
<i>and they're all just down there</i>

46:23.600 --> 46:27.400
<i>crying and all that,</i>
<i>watching him.</i>

46:28.600 --> 46:31.520
There was no problem
with women.

46:31.520 --> 46:34.720
You know, I'll tell you
a funny story. One day,

46:34.720 --> 46:38.120
I'm down in the lobby
of the Mayfair Hotel,

46:38.120 --> 46:41.120
and he comes walking in
out of the cab

46:41.120 --> 46:44.520
with this really
nice-looking woman.

46:44.520 --> 46:48.440
And they disappear,
come down a couple hours later,

46:48.440 --> 46:52.040
and they're having drinks
in the lobby,

46:52.040 --> 46:54.280
this bar there.

46:54.280 --> 46:58.680
And she leaves,
and then he makes a phone call.

46:58.680 --> 47:00.080
About a half hour later,

47:00.080 --> 47:02.120
he comes back
with a different woman. Ha!

47:02.120 --> 47:05.840
And they go up. They're gone.
This is in one afternoon.

47:05.840 --> 47:07.480
[CHUCKLES]

47:08.680 --> 47:11.120
Hello. How are you?

47:11.120 --> 47:13.840
DONOVAN:
<i>He had to have</i>
<i>a woman all the time.</i>

47:13.840 --> 47:17.240
<i>This guy traveled the world.</i>
<i>He knew, uh,</i>

47:17.240 --> 47:20.800
<i>women and people</i>
<i>in Paris and London</i>

47:20.800 --> 47:23.320
<i>and all those places, right?</i>

47:23.320 --> 47:26.080
<i>He'd go,</i>
<i>"Let me just call so-and-so."</i>

47:27.920 --> 47:30.720
Yeah, there was
no problem there.

47:30.720 --> 47:33.240
In fact, everybody
was doing pretty good.

47:33.240 --> 47:35.160
Even me.

47:35.160 --> 47:36.880
Oh, yeah.

47:39.840 --> 47:41.960
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

47:52.080 --> 47:56.480
COHEN:
<i>I had a great appetite</i>
<i>for the company of women</i>

47:56.480 --> 48:00.600
<i>and for the sexual expression</i>
<i>of friendship.</i>

48:00.600 --> 48:05.240
<i>And I was very fortunate,</i>
<i>because it was the '60s,</i>

48:05.240 --> 48:10.640
<i>and that possibility</i>
<i>was very, very present.</i>

48:10.640 --> 48:14.320
<i>And for a tiny moment</i>
<i>in social history,</i>

48:14.320 --> 48:16.080
<i>there was</i>
<i>a tremendous cooperation</i>

48:16.080 --> 48:21.360
<i>between men and women</i>
<i>about that particular item.</i>

48:21.360 --> 48:23.600
<i>And so I was very lucky that--</i>

48:23.600 --> 48:29.200
<i>That my appetite coincided</i>
<i>with this very rare--</i>

48:29.200 --> 48:30.880
<i>What, religious? Social?</i>

48:30.880 --> 48:32.840
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>what you'd call it.</i>

48:32.840 --> 48:35.080
<i>Some kind of phenomenon,</i>
<i>you know,</i>

48:35.080 --> 48:39.160
<i>that allowed men and women...</i>
<i>Boys and girls, we were.</i>

48:39.160 --> 48:41.480
<i>...to come together</i>
<i>in that kind of union</i>

48:41.480 --> 48:44.760
<i>that satisfied</i>
<i>both the appetites.</i>

48:48.440 --> 48:50.880
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

48:54.400 --> 48:59.080
♪ Like a bird ♪

48:59.080 --> 49:02.120
♪ On the wire ♪

49:02.120 --> 49:04.440
♪ Like a drunk in some ♪

49:04.440 --> 49:08.040
♪ Old midnight choir ♪

49:08.040 --> 49:10.960
♪ I have tried ♪

49:10.960 --> 49:14.200
♪ In my way ♪

49:14.200 --> 49:18.400
♪ To be free ♪

49:18.400 --> 49:21.240
IHLEN [IN ENGLISH]:
<i>I felt much more</i>
<i>that "Bird on a Wire"</i>

49:21.240 --> 49:25.480
<i>had something to do with me,</i>
<i>because I was there.</i>

49:25.480 --> 49:30.080
<i>When you see it in the light</i>
<i>of how it began,</i>

49:30.080 --> 49:34.480
<i>it was when the new electricity</i>
<i>came to Hydra.</i>

49:34.480 --> 49:37.120
<i>I gave him a guitar.</i>
<i>We looked out of the window.</i>

49:37.120 --> 49:40.120
<i>We saw the birds</i>
<i>landing on the wires.</i>

49:40.120 --> 49:43.320
<i>And he had not been able</i>
<i>to create or write or sing</i>

49:43.320 --> 49:44.920
<i>or do anything for weeks,</i>

49:44.920 --> 49:49.040
<i>and he was in a very,</i>
<i>very deep, deep depression.</i>

49:51.520 --> 49:53.920
<i>And it also was</i>
<i>a period in my life</i>

49:53.920 --> 49:55.920
<i>where I had to...</i>

49:57.240 --> 50:00.280
<i>make a decision</i>
<i>that was pretty hard.</i>

50:02.200 --> 50:07.280
<i>And that was following</i>
<i>my intuition...</i>

50:07.280 --> 50:09.440
<i>and decide that Leonard and I</i>

50:09.440 --> 50:14.000
<i>was not going to have</i>
<i>any children together.</i>

50:16.600 --> 50:18.560
<i>Yeah.</i>

50:18.560 --> 50:20.240
<i>[SNIFFLES]</i>

50:27.040 --> 50:29.920
BROOMFIELD:
<i>Marianne came</i>
<i>and visited me in Cardiff,</i>

50:29.920 --> 50:33.360
<i>where I was a student</i>
<i>living down by the docks.</i>

50:33.360 --> 50:35.600
<i>I was concerned</i>
<i>she might get bored,</i>

50:35.600 --> 50:39.120
<i>but Marianne was naturally</i>
<i>interested in everyone.</i>

50:39.120 --> 50:41.680
<i>She regarded being</i>
<i>receptive and open</i>

50:41.680 --> 50:43.800
<i>as the highest of qualities.</i>

50:43.800 --> 50:46.560
<i>Marianne made friends with</i>
<i>all the kids in the street,</i>

50:46.560 --> 50:48.840
<i>who followed her</i>
<i>around all day,</i>

50:48.840 --> 50:51.520
<i>and she encouraged me to</i>
<i>make my very first film</i>

50:51.520 --> 50:53.040
<i>on slum clearance,</i>

50:53.040 --> 50:56.920
<i>as the whole community</i>
<i>was being torn down.</i>

50:56.920 --> 50:59.520
<i>Marianne liked to throw</i>
<i>the I Ching every day</i>

50:59.520 --> 51:01.080
<i>and get stoned.</i>

51:01.080 --> 51:03.800
<i>She talked</i>
<i>about Leonard a lot:</i>

51:03.800 --> 51:07.400
<i>his favorite salt-beef</i>
<i>sandwich shop in Piccadilly,</i>

51:07.400 --> 51:09.200
<i>his spiritual search,</i>

51:09.200 --> 51:12.640
<i>even dabbling</i>
<i>in Scientology and est.</i>

51:12.640 --> 51:15.760
<i>Marianne, too, was on</i>
<i>her own spiritual search,</i>

51:15.760 --> 51:19.200
<i>and Leonard was,</i>
<i>in many ways, her teacher.</i>

51:19.200 --> 51:22.720
<i>One day she asked me</i>
<i>to drive her to Bath.</i>

51:22.720 --> 51:26.800
<i>She said she was pregnant</i>
<i>with Leonard's child.</i>

51:26.800 --> 51:29.280
I think she was preg--
She was pregnant.

51:29.280 --> 51:31.720
But she knew that Leonard
didn't want children,

51:31.720 --> 51:34.120
and she had abortions
even though she would have--

51:34.120 --> 51:38.120
If anyone should have had
Leonard's children,

51:38.120 --> 51:39.880
she deserved to have them.

51:39.880 --> 51:42.840
But she didn't,
for Leonard's sake.

51:42.840 --> 51:47.200
But, you know,
she wanted what I wanted.

51:47.200 --> 51:50.400
She wanted to...

51:50.400 --> 51:52.320
She wanted to be with him.

51:52.320 --> 51:56.360
And you cannot be
with Leonard...

51:57.800 --> 52:00.560
in that sense.

52:00.560 --> 52:03.440
Although you could say
that I'd rather have one day

52:03.440 --> 52:05.000
or one night with Leonard

52:05.000 --> 52:06.680
than a lifetime
with somebody else.

52:06.680 --> 52:09.080
That would be easy to say,
but it's not--

52:09.080 --> 52:10.840
It's not so easy, you know?

52:10.840 --> 52:13.960
I could have said that
with Irving, just to be--

52:13.960 --> 52:16.920
I was with Irving
for over 20 years.

52:16.920 --> 52:19.440
Whatever the ups and downs,
how wonderful it was--

52:19.440 --> 52:24.440
And it was, but most
of that time was anguish.

52:24.440 --> 52:26.080
You can't--
BROOMFIELD: Anguish?

52:26.080 --> 52:29.880
Well, you know, it was
the days of open marriage,

52:29.880 --> 52:31.440
whatever the hell that was,

52:31.440 --> 52:35.760
and I don't think it ever
was successful with anybody.

52:35.760 --> 52:39.000
One of the partners
was always jealous

52:39.000 --> 52:41.960
and angry
and hurt and confused.

52:41.960 --> 52:44.560
<i>I don't know any child</i>
<i>who came out of it</i>

52:44.560 --> 52:46.480
<i>not damaged</i>
<i>by that period of time.</i>

52:46.480 --> 52:48.840
<i>We just wanted to</i>
<i>do it all: take drugs</i>

52:48.840 --> 52:51.240
<i>and fuck around</i>
<i>and do whatever we liked,</i>

52:51.240 --> 52:55.120
<i>and the children were just--</i>
<i>They came along on the ride.</i>

52:55.120 --> 52:58.320
<i>They didn't want to</i>
<i>come along on that ride.</i>

52:58.320 --> 53:00.200
BROWN:
<i>There are a lot of us</i>

53:00.200 --> 53:03.240
<i>who grew up</i>
<i>very quickly on the island.</i>

53:03.240 --> 53:05.480
<i>There was also a lot of acid</i>
<i>on the island.</i>

53:05.480 --> 53:08.000
<i>Like, people were</i>
<i>actually dropping acid</i>

53:08.000 --> 53:09.440
<i>into people's drinks.</i>

53:09.440 --> 53:12.440
<i>And I remember</i>
<i>hearing reports of people</i>

53:12.440 --> 53:14.480
<i>um, having donkeys--</i>

53:14.480 --> 53:18.000
<i>They were riding donkeys</i>
<i>that, like, started tripping</i>

53:18.000 --> 53:20.120
<i>and getting into all kinds</i>
<i>of trouble,</i>

53:20.120 --> 53:21.880
<i>you know,</i>
<i>and accidents, uh, riding--</i>

53:21.880 --> 53:23.760
BROOMFIELD:
<i>They gave acid to donkeys?</i>

53:23.760 --> 53:25.640
BROWN:
<i>Yeah, as well as to people.</i>

53:25.640 --> 53:29.000
<i>I got-- Someone put acid</i>
<i>in one of my drinks</i>

53:29.000 --> 53:30.880
<i>when I was about 13,</i>

53:30.880 --> 53:33.600
<i>and I had no idea</i>
<i>what was happening.</i>

53:35.120 --> 53:37.160
<i>Also a lot</i>
<i>of casualties happened.</i>

53:37.160 --> 53:41.320
<i>I think Marianne and,</i>
<i>um, a lot of other women</i>

53:41.320 --> 53:45.320
<i>were not as nurturing</i>
<i>to their children, perhaps,</i>

53:45.320 --> 53:48.560
<i>or as present with them</i>
<i>as they could have been.</i>

53:48.560 --> 53:52.800
<i>Axel was really</i>
<i>a casualty of that.</i>

53:52.800 --> 53:56.000
<i>Marianne was going from one</i>
<i>love to another, to another,</i>

53:56.000 --> 53:59.360
<i>and often he wasn't with her.</i>

53:59.360 --> 54:02.440
<i>You know, so who was he with?</i>
<i>And Leonard--</i>

54:02.440 --> 54:05.480
<i>You know,</i>
<i>he wasn't Leonard's kid.</i>

54:05.480 --> 54:08.280
<i>He started wearing long, um,</i>

54:08.280 --> 54:10.720
<i>you know,</i>
<i>flowing Moroccan robes,</i>

54:10.720 --> 54:13.240
<i>and he was silent for years.</i>

54:13.240 --> 54:17.480
<i>And then later he became</i>
<i>institutionalized.</i>

54:17.480 --> 54:20.640
<i>But I've always felt very sad</i>
<i>that he's been, you know,</i>

54:20.640 --> 54:24.520
<i>institutionalized for most</i>
<i>of his adult life.</i>

54:26.360 --> 54:30.240
Those who could work
with Hydra did really well.

54:30.240 --> 54:32.360
And there weren't many,
quite frankly.

54:32.360 --> 54:34.880
I saw so many artists who came

54:34.880 --> 54:37.520
and either just found
their creativity

54:37.520 --> 54:40.840
just wasn't strong enough
to sustain them,

54:40.840 --> 54:44.920
or the booze, the sex,
the beauty of the landscape

54:44.920 --> 54:47.280
was all too much,
and they just gave up.

54:47.280 --> 54:50.280
But Leonard was one
of those who-- Who somehow--

54:50.280 --> 54:54.040
The whole environment,
I think, sort of coalesced

54:54.040 --> 54:56.720
and worked for him,
and he worked with it.

54:56.720 --> 54:58.640
Heh. Still, we have to go.

54:58.640 --> 55:02.400
COHEN:
♪ I've got a home
In glory land ♪

55:02.400 --> 55:07.880
ALL:
♪ That outshines the sun ♪

55:07.880 --> 55:12.640
♪ I got a home in glory land ♪

55:12.640 --> 55:17.360
♪ That outshines the sun ♪

55:18.600 --> 55:22.560
♪ I got a home in glory land ♪

55:22.560 --> 55:27.680
♪ That outshines the sun ♪

55:27.680 --> 55:32.280
♪ Must be the hand ♪

55:32.280 --> 55:34.640
♪ Of the Lord ♪

55:35.800 --> 55:39.240
♪ Oh, do Lord, Oh, do Lord... ♪

55:39.240 --> 55:42.720
GOLDMAN:
<i>He was a real success story.</i>
<i>He really was.</i>

55:42.720 --> 55:46.600
<i>He wasn't damaged</i>
<i>by that place, I think, at all.</i>

55:46.600 --> 55:51.280
Many other people seemed
to come away from that place

55:51.280 --> 55:55.560
sort of irreparably damaged.

55:55.560 --> 55:58.280
And it was terrible
on marriages.

55:58.280 --> 56:01.800
Very few marriages
lasted at that place,

56:01.800 --> 56:03.520
including my parents'.

56:03.520 --> 56:06.000
[♪♪♪]

56:09.160 --> 56:11.240
BROOMFIELD:
<i>I remember Marianne telling me</i>

56:11.240 --> 56:13.440
<i>of the tragedy</i>
<i>of the Johnstons,</i>

56:13.440 --> 56:17.440
<i>the family that Leonard had</i>
<i>originally stayed with in 1960,</i>

56:17.440 --> 56:21.600
<i>who left the island</i>
<i>after nine years.</i>

56:21.600 --> 56:25.200
GOLDMAN:
<i>This family of such</i>
<i>amazing talent and promise,</i>

56:25.200 --> 56:27.920
<i>and they just kind of</i>
<i>all fell to bits</i>

56:27.920 --> 56:29.880
<i>shortly after</i>
<i>leaving the island.</i>

56:29.880 --> 56:31.080
It's my birthday today,

56:31.080 --> 56:32.840
and this is
a wonderful homecoming.

56:32.840 --> 56:34.840
And that was a photograph,
a family one,

56:34.840 --> 56:37.920
taken on my birthday
last year on the island.

56:37.920 --> 56:40.360
[BOTH SPEAKING IN GREEK]

56:43.000 --> 56:45.440
They always speak Greek
among themselves.

56:45.440 --> 56:47.760
I think it comes
more naturally to them.

56:47.760 --> 56:50.920
And they've done all their
schooling in Greece, ten years.

56:50.920 --> 56:54.920
GOLDMAN:
<i>When they left,</i>
<i>almost penniless,</i>

56:54.920 --> 56:58.960
<i>she killed herself, like,</i>
<i>a couple years later.</i>

56:58.960 --> 57:01.200
<i>He died a year after that</i>

57:01.200 --> 57:04.040
<i>of tuberculosis,</i>
<i>probably greatly compounded</i>

57:04.040 --> 57:07.760
<i>by cigarettes and alcohol.</i>

57:07.760 --> 57:10.560
<i>And then the children that--</i>
<i>That had--</i>

57:10.560 --> 57:13.040
<i>That seemed</i>
<i>so, you know, glorious</i>

57:13.040 --> 57:15.760
<i>and beautiful and bright</i>
<i>and wonderful on the island,</i>

57:15.760 --> 57:17.600
<i>they, one by one, died early</i>

57:17.600 --> 57:20.160
<i>of alcoholism,</i>
<i>suicide, drugs.</i>

57:20.160 --> 57:21.960
<i>There's only one that's alive.</i>

57:21.960 --> 57:25.760
[♪♪♪]

57:25.760 --> 57:27.960
SLATER:
<i>Numerous other children</i>

57:27.960 --> 57:30.080
<i>from families</i>
<i>that had lived on Hydra</i>

57:30.080 --> 57:35.120
<i>have had a hard time</i>
<i>re-entering the real world.</i>

57:35.120 --> 57:38.440
<i>I think there is</i>
<i>a depression that sets in</i>

57:38.440 --> 57:40.160
<i>if you've spent any time there.</i>

57:40.160 --> 57:41.760
<i>I've certainly felt it.</i>

57:41.760 --> 57:44.440
<i>There's not a day that goes by</i>
<i>that I don't wake up</i>

57:44.440 --> 57:47.360
<i>and wish that I were there,</i>
<i>you know?</i>

57:47.360 --> 57:50.040
<i>Literally.</i>
<i>I never wanted to be</i>

57:50.040 --> 57:52.720
<i>any other place</i>
<i>in the world, you know?</i>

57:54.120 --> 57:56.720
<i>It's just the place.</i>

57:56.720 --> 57:58.880
<i>It's just the place, you know?</i>

57:58.880 --> 58:03.560
<i>Uh, you--</i>
<i>It gets in your bones.</i>

58:03.560 --> 58:05.560
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>how to describe it,</i>

58:05.560 --> 58:08.080
<i>but it's just</i> the<i> place.</i>

58:08.080 --> 58:11.160
<i>Just stepping off</i>
<i>the boat, every time,</i>

58:11.160 --> 58:14.240
<i>it's, uh, coming home.</i>

58:16.560 --> 58:18.960
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

58:33.000 --> 58:35.400
CORNELIUS:
<i>That was a very weird,</i>
<i>weird night.</i>

58:35.400 --> 58:38.640
<i>There were 660,000 people</i>
<i>out there.</i>

58:40.160 --> 58:42.680
<i>It was a disturbing night.</i>

58:45.960 --> 58:48.480
<i>They even caught</i>
<i>the stage on fire.</i>

58:48.480 --> 58:52.000
<i>Had to put the stage out</i>
<i>before we went on.</i>

58:52.000 --> 58:54.520
<i>"Maybe we out to get</i>
<i>out of here, you know?</i>

58:54.520 --> 58:56.600
<i>Somebody's gonna get hurt."</i>

58:57.680 --> 58:59.560
<i>Leonard embraced it.</i>

58:59.560 --> 59:01.720
<i>He got into it.</i>

59:01.720 --> 59:03.240
<i>Like I was saying before,</i>

59:03.240 --> 59:05.840
<i>you either get 'em</i>
<i>or you don't.</i>

59:05.840 --> 59:07.760
<i>He got 'em.</i>

59:12.560 --> 59:14.920
COHEN:
<i>I was on Mandrax at the time.</i>

59:14.920 --> 59:18.400
<i>They used to call me</i>
<i>Captain Mandrax.</i>

59:18.400 --> 59:21.360
<i>I think it-- It had--</i>
<i>It was like a Quaalude.</i>

59:21.360 --> 59:26.520
<i>I was relaxed beyond</i>
<i>any reasonable state.</i>

59:26.520 --> 59:29.320
I hope she's here, Marianne.

59:29.320 --> 59:31.440
I hope she's here.
Maybe she's here.

59:31.440 --> 59:33.960
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

59:33.960 --> 59:37.960
I hope she's here. Marianne.

59:39.640 --> 59:43.440
[BAND STARTS PLAYING
"THE PARTISAN"]

59:43.440 --> 59:47.160
♪ An old woman
Gave us shelter ♪

59:47.160 --> 59:50.600
♪ Kept us hidden
In the garret ♪

59:50.600 --> 59:54.560
♪ Then the soldiers came... ♪

59:54.560 --> 59:58.400
IHLEN [IN NORWEGIAN]:
<i>How long could we stay in love</i>

59:58.400 --> 1:00:01.440
<i>before we had</i>
<i>to address our problems?</i>

1:00:01.440 --> 1:00:05.560
<i>I recognized</i>
<i>the situation we were in.</i>

1:00:05.560 --> 1:00:10.520
<i>We couldn't communicate</i>
<i>together any more.</i>

1:00:10.520 --> 1:00:13.120
<i>We were getting nowhere.</i>

1:00:13.120 --> 1:00:16.400
<i>We couldn't understand</i>
<i>what the other was saying.</i>

1:00:16.400 --> 1:00:18.760
<i>Leonard naturally</i>
<i>immersed himself</i>

1:00:18.760 --> 1:00:20.800
<i>in his writing and music.</i>

1:00:20.800 --> 1:00:22.840
<i>We tried and we tried.</i>

1:00:22.840 --> 1:00:25.960
<i>Neither of us wanted</i>
<i>to give up completely.</i>

1:00:29.480 --> 1:00:33.360
CORNELIUS:
<i>And Marianne was--</i>
<i>Was, uh, one woman</i>

1:00:33.360 --> 1:00:36.040
that didn't seem to me

1:00:36.040 --> 1:00:38.680
all starstruck over Leonard.

1:00:40.280 --> 1:00:43.400
Kind of held her own.
Put it that way, you know?

1:00:45.200 --> 1:00:48.480
<i>She would join us sometimes</i>
<i>for a week at a time</i>

1:00:48.480 --> 1:00:51.800
<i>or maybe ten days</i>
<i>at a time and be gone.</i>

1:00:51.800 --> 1:00:55.640
<i>There was other ladies</i>
<i>that Leonard had on tour.</i>

1:00:55.640 --> 1:00:58.000
<i>But when Marianne was in town,</i>

1:00:58.000 --> 1:01:00.360
<i>he was out of the picture.</i>

1:01:00.360 --> 1:01:04.440
<i>She carried with her</i>
<i>a different feel than any woman</i>

1:01:04.440 --> 1:01:07.040
<i>that I ever saw around Leonard.</i>

1:01:07.040 --> 1:01:09.480
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

1:01:15.400 --> 1:01:19.080
<i>There was a, uh--</i>
<i>A need for</i>

1:01:19.080 --> 1:01:22.400
<i>such a connection between</i>
<i>Leonard and his audience</i>

1:01:22.400 --> 1:01:25.640
<i>that would actually</i>
<i>have blown your mind.</i>

1:01:25.640 --> 1:01:27.720
<i>One night he had, uh,</i>

1:01:27.720 --> 1:01:30.520
<i>so many people</i>
<i>come up on stage with him</i>

1:01:30.520 --> 1:01:34.400
<i>that it was like</i>
<i>this big love-in</i>

1:01:34.400 --> 1:01:37.200
<i>right in the middle</i>
<i>of our concert.</i>

1:01:41.920 --> 1:01:45.320
<i>Like, a pile of people</i>
<i>making love</i>

1:01:45.320 --> 1:01:47.040
<i>without taking</i>
<i>their clothes off.</i>

1:01:47.040 --> 1:01:50.000
<i>But if we could've</i>
<i>stuck around a while longer,</i>

1:01:50.000 --> 1:01:52.720
<i>who knows</i>
<i>what would've happened?</i>

1:01:59.800 --> 1:02:02.400
<i>Can you imagine?</i>
<i>We're playing Amsterdam,</i>

1:02:02.400 --> 1:02:06.040
<i>and he invites</i>
<i>the entire audience</i>

1:02:06.040 --> 1:02:10.040
<i>to come home with us</i>
<i>to his hotel.</i>

1:02:10.040 --> 1:02:11.920
<i>And they did it.</i>

1:02:15.920 --> 1:02:20.160
<i>We took a lot of acid</i>
<i>on those trips. A lot.</i>

1:02:20.160 --> 1:02:22.160
<i>Leonard had a buddy in London,</i>

1:02:22.160 --> 1:02:25.680
<i>and he had a thing</i>
<i>called desert dust.</i>

1:02:25.680 --> 1:02:28.840
<i>And if you took a needle...</i>

1:02:29.760 --> 1:02:31.680
and touched it to your tongue,

1:02:31.680 --> 1:02:34.320
and the tiniest little speck

1:02:34.320 --> 1:02:37.040
that you could pick up
with that needle

1:02:37.040 --> 1:02:39.440
on your tongue, gone.

1:02:39.440 --> 1:02:42.240
I mean, gone for 14 hours,

1:02:42.240 --> 1:02:45.280
with no reentry, none.

1:02:45.280 --> 1:02:48.440
One time we took
that damn desert dust

1:02:48.440 --> 1:02:50.360
23 nights in a row,

1:02:50.360 --> 1:02:54.240
playing the Royal Albert Hall
and the Vienna Opera House

1:02:54.240 --> 1:02:56.440
and all the fine places on the--

1:02:56.440 --> 1:03:00.320
I mean, I gotta tell you,
there's no way I could--

1:03:00.320 --> 1:03:02.200
I could ever even survive

1:03:02.200 --> 1:03:04.480
one of those nights
at this point.

1:03:04.480 --> 1:03:06.640
Wanna see my text here?

1:03:07.600 --> 1:03:10.480
BAND MEMBERS:
Hey!

1:03:10.480 --> 1:03:12.880
[WOMAN SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY]

1:03:15.440 --> 1:03:17.560
MAN:
This is the way
it's gotta be done.

1:03:17.560 --> 1:03:19.600
COHEN: Think that still works?
MAN: I don't know.

1:03:19.600 --> 1:03:22.400
I'll be in serious trouble
if it works or doesn't work.

1:03:22.400 --> 1:03:24.080
Right.
[LAUGHS]

1:03:24.080 --> 1:03:25.720
CORNELIUS:
<i>Leonard used to say</i>

1:03:25.720 --> 1:03:28.080
<i>you have to be in the zone.</i>

1:03:28.080 --> 1:03:31.720
<i>Well, we stayed in the zone.</i>
<i>A lot of people would think,</i>

1:03:31.720 --> 1:03:34.280
<i>well, if you burn it down</i>
<i>really strong tonight,</i>

1:03:34.280 --> 1:03:37.440
<i>tomorrow morning you got</i>
<i>that hangover and all that.</i>

1:03:37.440 --> 1:03:40.160
<i>Uh-uh. We stayed in the zone...</i>

1:03:40.160 --> 1:03:42.800
<i>day after day after day.</i>

1:03:42.800 --> 1:03:44.720
<i>There was only one night,</i>

1:03:44.720 --> 1:03:46.920
<i>we were playing in Jerusalem,</i>

1:03:46.920 --> 1:03:50.160
<i>when he wasn't getting 'em.</i>

1:03:50.160 --> 1:03:53.480
Now look, uh,
if it doesn't get any better,

1:03:53.480 --> 1:03:57.120
uh, we'll just end the concert
and I'll refund your money.

1:03:57.120 --> 1:03:59.560
Some nights...

1:03:59.560 --> 1:04:02.480
one is raised off the ground.

1:04:02.480 --> 1:04:06.280
And some nights, you just
can't get off the ground.

1:04:06.280 --> 1:04:08.560
And there's no point
in lying about it.

1:04:08.560 --> 1:04:11.280
And tonight we just haven't
been getting off the ground.

1:04:11.280 --> 1:04:13.560
DONOVAN:
<i>So anyway, we're backstage,</i>

1:04:13.560 --> 1:04:15.640
<i>and we're going,</i>
<i>"Well, what's gonna happen?"</i>

1:04:15.640 --> 1:04:18.560
And Marty Machat, his manager,
is trying to talk to him.

1:04:18.560 --> 1:04:23.000
And Leonard's just zinging,
right? I knew that. And, uh--

1:04:23.000 --> 1:04:24.720
BROOMFIELD:
How do you mean, "zinging"?

1:04:24.720 --> 1:04:26.960
I mean, like on LSD.

1:04:26.960 --> 1:04:30.680
Like, his eyes are blacked out,
like they get, right?

1:04:30.680 --> 1:04:34.280
And, uh, he's just feeling--

1:04:34.280 --> 1:04:38.240
And so all of a sudden
he says to me, he goes,

1:04:38.240 --> 1:04:41.600
"Billy, can you get me a razor?"

1:04:41.600 --> 1:04:44.520
I said, "Leonard, what are you
gonna do, cut your throat?"

1:04:44.520 --> 1:04:47.240
And he said,
"No. I think if I shave,

1:04:47.240 --> 1:04:49.160
I might be able to go back out."

1:04:49.160 --> 1:04:51.160
MAN:
This is the last concert,
you know?

1:04:51.160 --> 1:04:53.600
This is something you have
to do, and then bang--

1:04:53.600 --> 1:04:56.440
Oh, I know what I have to do.
I have to shave.

1:04:56.440 --> 1:04:57.680
What a life.

1:04:57.680 --> 1:04:58.960
[CHUCKLES]

1:04:58.960 --> 1:05:00.600
What a life.

1:05:02.080 --> 1:05:04.640
Oh, this is wonderful.

1:05:04.640 --> 1:05:07.120
Why didn't you tell me
about this?

1:05:07.120 --> 1:05:09.480
[ALL LAUGHING]

1:05:12.200 --> 1:05:14.840
DONOVAN:
<i>So that's what he did.</i>
<i>He shaved...</i>

1:05:14.840 --> 1:05:19.240
<i>Dry-shaved, almost, ha,</i>
<i>with just some water.</i>

1:05:19.240 --> 1:05:21.120
<i>...and then</i>
<i>he went back out there</i>

1:05:21.120 --> 1:05:23.120
<i>with a big rash on his face</i>

1:05:23.120 --> 1:05:24.920
<i>and finished the show.</i>

1:05:24.920 --> 1:05:27.680
You ought to try it, man.
It's wonderful.

1:05:29.560 --> 1:05:33.720
Oh, yeah.
Oh, this is really great.

1:05:33.720 --> 1:05:38.480
♪ I saw Jesus on the cross ♪

1:05:38.480 --> 1:05:42.480
♪ On a hill called Calvary ♪

1:05:42.480 --> 1:05:45.200
♪ Do you hate mankind ♪

1:05:45.200 --> 1:05:48.120
♪ For what they've done
To you? ♪

1:05:49.440 --> 1:05:54.400
♪ He said
Talk of love, not hate... ♪

1:05:54.400 --> 1:05:57.280
CORNELIUS:
<i>Everybody was shooting</i>
<i>from the hip, right?</i>

1:05:57.280 --> 1:06:01.400
<i>Not-- Not welded to anything.</i>

1:06:01.400 --> 1:06:06.600
<i>The idea was that tonight</i>
<i>we will play this song</i>

1:06:06.600 --> 1:06:09.080
<i>better than we did last night.</i>

1:06:09.080 --> 1:06:11.560
<i>And tomorrow night,</i>
<i>we're gonna play it better</i>

1:06:11.560 --> 1:06:12.960
<i>than we did tonight.</i>

1:06:12.960 --> 1:06:16.960
ALL:
♪ Sometimes happy
Sometimes blue ♪

1:06:16.960 --> 1:06:18.920
♪ Glad that I ran... ♪

1:06:18.920 --> 1:06:21.760
<i>There was only one night,</i>
<i>one night,</i>

1:06:21.760 --> 1:06:25.480
<i>that I felt like</i>
<i>that I let things</i>

1:06:25.480 --> 1:06:27.560
<i>get away from me.</i>

1:06:27.560 --> 1:06:32.120
And I actually went for this--
This beautiful chord--

1:06:32.120 --> 1:06:35.120
It was an F-sharp
minor seventh, I think,

1:06:35.120 --> 1:06:37.880
in the song called "Suzanne,"

1:06:37.880 --> 1:06:40.960
and as I went for that chord,

1:06:40.960 --> 1:06:43.400
I actually landed on my face

1:06:43.400 --> 1:06:46.120
on the ground--
On the stage right there.

1:06:46.120 --> 1:06:48.920
And Leonard turned around
and looked at me like,

1:06:48.920 --> 1:06:53.240
"Okay, we need to now start
backing off the Mandrax, right?"

1:06:53.240 --> 1:06:56.840
[♪♪♪]

1:06:56.840 --> 1:07:00.840
BROOMFIELD:
<i>Marianne and I kept in touch</i>
<i>during the '70s and '80s</i>

1:07:00.840 --> 1:07:03.840
<i>with the occasional</i>
<i>postcard and letter.</i>

1:07:03.840 --> 1:07:05.960
<i>I was delighted</i>
<i>when she suggested</i>

1:07:05.960 --> 1:07:07.400
<i>we might work together,</i>

1:07:07.400 --> 1:07:10.320
<i>and we talked about</i>
<i>various ideas.</i>

1:07:10.320 --> 1:07:13.680
<i>Marianne was increasingly</i>
<i>concerned about Axel.</i>

1:07:13.680 --> 1:07:17.280
<i>He'd been on a trip to India</i>
<i>and taken too many drugs.</i>

1:07:17.280 --> 1:07:19.720
<i>She was upset</i>
<i>with Little Axel's father,</i>

1:07:19.720 --> 1:07:21.400
<i>who had encouraged him.</i>

1:07:21.400 --> 1:07:25.080
<i>Axel was now living</i>
<i>in an institution in Oslo,</i>

1:07:25.080 --> 1:07:28.440
<i>and Marianne was spending</i>
<i>more and more time with him.</i>

1:07:28.440 --> 1:07:30.440
<i>Marianne had still been</i>
<i>following Leonard</i>

1:07:30.440 --> 1:07:32.920
<i>on his travels,</i>
<i>and very infrequently,</i>

1:07:32.920 --> 1:07:36.640
<i>they still shared the house</i>
<i>together on Hydra.</i>

1:07:36.640 --> 1:07:38.480
<i>Apparently Leonard</i>
<i>was now living</i>

1:07:38.480 --> 1:07:40.120
<i>part of the year in Montreal</i>

1:07:40.120 --> 1:07:43.160
<i>with a woman called Suzanne.</i>

1:07:43.160 --> 1:07:45.520
SCOTT:
<i>I've read three</i>
<i>of his biographies,</i>

1:07:45.520 --> 1:07:46.920
<i>and I've always been surprised</i>

1:07:46.920 --> 1:07:49.600
<i>that they sort of</i>
<i>partition it as, like,</i>

1:07:49.600 --> 1:07:52.480
<i>"Okay, here was Marianne,</i>
<i>and then that was over,</i>

1:07:52.480 --> 1:07:54.400
<i>and then he took up</i>
<i>with Suzanne."</i>

1:07:54.400 --> 1:07:58.000
<i>But in fact, there was</i>
<i>a considerable overlap of time</i>

1:07:58.000 --> 1:08:01.840
<i>where he supported</i>
<i>both families.</i>

1:08:01.840 --> 1:08:05.400
<i>He said that when he was</i>
<i>with her and Axel</i>

1:08:05.400 --> 1:08:08.400
<i>in that house on Hydra, he felt</i>
<i>that's where he belonged.</i>

1:08:08.400 --> 1:08:12.640
<i>But when he was with Suzanne</i>
<i>and the baby in Montreal,</i>

1:08:12.640 --> 1:08:14.840
<i>he felt</i>
<i>that's where he belonged.</i>

1:08:14.840 --> 1:08:17.840
<i>And so he was confused.</i>

1:08:17.840 --> 1:08:21.920
<i>Suzanne, she was much</i>
<i>more visceral, in a way,</i>

1:08:21.920 --> 1:08:25.360
<i>and, uh, 14 years younger</i>
<i>than him.</i>

1:08:25.360 --> 1:08:28.320
<i>So I guess there was a whole</i>
<i>bunch of different things</i>

1:08:28.320 --> 1:08:32.240
<i>that, uh, conspired to--</i>

1:08:32.240 --> 1:08:34.400
<i>To make it come to an end.</i>

1:08:35.720 --> 1:08:39.560
You needed somebody
like Suzanne, who was...

1:08:39.560 --> 1:08:40.880
Well, the word "ruthless"

1:08:40.880 --> 1:08:44.520
is just the word that--
That comes to mind.

1:08:44.520 --> 1:08:47.400
And she did
what she wanted to do

1:08:47.400 --> 1:08:52.200
to bind Leonard to her
by any means.

1:08:52.200 --> 1:08:56.120
She used the Black Panther
theme, "By any means necessary."

1:08:56.120 --> 1:08:58.680
And, boy, did she do--

1:08:58.680 --> 1:09:02.960
And she knew exactly
what to do and when to do it.

1:09:02.960 --> 1:09:06.560
It was like falling
into a spider's web.

1:09:06.560 --> 1:09:07.880
There was something--

1:09:07.880 --> 1:09:10.040
There's always something
terribly fascinating

1:09:10.040 --> 1:09:11.560
about the spider.

1:09:11.560 --> 1:09:14.080
Very fascinating.

1:09:14.080 --> 1:09:18.360
And I think Leonard
just fell into that

1:09:18.360 --> 1:09:21.480
'cause it was so fascinating.

1:09:21.480 --> 1:09:24.440
I don't even know what drove
that whole thing, but he knew--

1:09:24.440 --> 1:09:27.360
He knew he was,
as Irving would say,

1:09:27.360 --> 1:09:29.360
"Make sure you're doing
the wrong thing."

1:09:29.360 --> 1:09:33.040
Boy, did he make sure he did
the wrong thing with Suzanne.

1:09:33.040 --> 1:09:36.160
[♪♪♪]

1:09:58.640 --> 1:10:00.960
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

1:10:03.160 --> 1:10:06.880
CORNELIUS:
<i>I think Leonard's quest in life</i>

1:10:06.880 --> 1:10:09.800
<i>overrode the normal,</i>
<i>you know, settling down</i>

1:10:09.800 --> 1:10:14.600
<i>and having a home and a family</i>
<i>and all that stuff.</i>

1:10:14.600 --> 1:10:18.480
<i>Leonard always had that feeling</i>
<i>that he was after something</i>

1:10:18.480 --> 1:10:22.480
<i>that he couldn't get</i>
<i>his hands around.</i>

1:10:22.480 --> 1:10:24.960
<i>The only thing about it is,</i>
<i>I don't know what he--</i>

1:10:24.960 --> 1:10:28.040
<i>I don't think he knew</i>
<i>what he was chasing, you know?</i>

1:10:28.040 --> 1:10:30.920
<i>I don't think he--</i>
<i>I don't think he really knew.</i>

1:10:30.920 --> 1:10:34.560
<i>And that made it</i>
<i>probably a darker--</i>

1:10:34.560 --> 1:10:38.960
<i>You know? He lived in a--</i>
<i>He lived in darkness.</i>

1:10:38.960 --> 1:10:41.200
<i>'Cause he'd disappear</i>
<i>for six weeks sometimes.</i>

1:10:41.200 --> 1:10:43.680
<i>I wouldn't know how to</i>
<i>find him or nothing.</i>

1:10:43.680 --> 1:10:45.240
<i>Nobody would, you know?</i>

1:10:45.240 --> 1:10:50.280
<i>And it was all</i>
<i>a deep, deep depression.</i>

1:10:50.280 --> 1:10:52.680
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

1:10:57.840 --> 1:11:00.920
LISSAUER:
<i>When we toured Europe</i>
<i>and when we toured Germany,</i>

1:11:00.920 --> 1:11:04.280
<i>I've never seen</i>
<i>so many blonds in one audience.</i>

1:11:04.280 --> 1:11:05.840
<i>He was the poet</i>

1:11:05.840 --> 1:11:08.480
<i>for the quasi-depressed women</i>
<i>of his era.</i>

1:11:08.480 --> 1:11:11.000
<i>People who were going through</i>
<i>issues, they'd come up sobbing,</i>

1:11:11.000 --> 1:11:13.560
<i>"You saved my life.</i>
<i>I was in such a dark place,</i>

1:11:13.560 --> 1:11:16.400
<i>and your darkness</i>
<i>led me out of it."</i>

1:11:16.400 --> 1:11:18.760
COHEN:
Thank you so much.

1:11:18.760 --> 1:11:22.080
LISSAUER:
<i>He had his thing</i>
<i>that he projected.</i>

1:11:22.080 --> 1:11:24.520
<i>He had his black suit.</i>

1:11:24.520 --> 1:11:26.560
<i>He had his look of seriousness.</i>

1:11:26.560 --> 1:11:30.680
<i>And you never saw his humor.</i>
<i>He was a really funny guy,</i>

1:11:30.680 --> 1:11:33.200
<i>but when he was on-stage,</i>
<i>it was dark,</i>

1:11:33.200 --> 1:11:37.720
<i>and it was lonely</i>
<i>and it was desperate.</i>

1:11:37.720 --> 1:11:41.080
--those who would sacrifice

1:11:41.080 --> 1:11:44.320
one generation
on behalf of another.

1:11:48.760 --> 1:11:52.440
♪ Well, the door
It opened slowly ♪

1:11:52.440 --> 1:11:55.040
♪ My father, he came in ♪

1:11:55.040 --> 1:11:58.560
♪ I was 9 years old ♪

1:11:59.680 --> 1:12:02.960
♪ And he stood
So tall above me ♪

1:12:02.960 --> 1:12:06.000
♪ And his blue eyes
They were shining ♪

1:12:06.000 --> 1:12:09.160
♪ And his voice
Was very cold... ♪

1:12:10.360 --> 1:12:11.960
LISSAUER:
<i>I wanted to--</i>

1:12:11.960 --> 1:12:15.320
<i>To frame each of the songs</i>

1:12:15.320 --> 1:12:19.200
<i>like, um, a little vignette.</i>

1:12:19.200 --> 1:12:21.040
They all had
these places of mind.

1:12:21.040 --> 1:12:22.600
So I was giving them colors.

1:12:22.600 --> 1:12:24.360
We were using
unusual instruments.

1:12:24.360 --> 1:12:27.480
We'd use a couple of muted
trombones to take it somewhere,

1:12:27.480 --> 1:12:30.400
or very icy strings

1:12:30.400 --> 1:12:34.360
and dark, shimmering things
to make it,

1:12:34.360 --> 1:12:36.400
uh, these little movies.

1:12:36.400 --> 1:12:38.280
And we came back,
we were ready to do

1:12:38.280 --> 1:12:40.120
another couple of weeks
in the studio,

1:12:40.120 --> 1:12:43.160
and he said, "I'm gonna go
to Hydra for a little bit.

1:12:43.160 --> 1:12:46.560
As soon as I get back,
we'll finish it."

1:12:46.560 --> 1:12:49.080
And I didn't hear from him

1:12:49.080 --> 1:12:52.040
for seven years.

1:12:53.560 --> 1:12:56.360
[♪♪♪]

1:13:00.000 --> 1:13:03.840
<i>It turns out Marty Machat,</i>
<i>who was Leonard's manager,</i>

1:13:03.840 --> 1:13:06.320
<i>also managed Phil Spector,</i>

1:13:06.320 --> 1:13:09.840
<i>and he had made a deal</i>
<i>for Phil with Warner Brothers</i>

1:13:09.840 --> 1:13:13.360
<i>that got them both</i>
<i>a huge advance.</i>

1:13:13.360 --> 1:13:14.680
<i>A really huge advance.</i>

1:13:14.680 --> 1:13:16.920
<i>For the '70s,</i>
<i>it was unheard of.</i>

1:13:16.920 --> 1:13:18.600
<i>So, what had happened is,</i>

1:13:18.600 --> 1:13:20.280
<i>Marty called up Leonard</i>
<i>and said,</i>

1:13:20.280 --> 1:13:22.240
<i>"Forget the record with John.</i>

1:13:22.240 --> 1:13:24.440
<i>We want you to do a record</i>
<i>with Phil Spector.</i>

1:13:24.440 --> 1:13:26.600
<i>He's really famous.</i>
<i>It'll make you a hit."</i>

1:13:26.600 --> 1:13:30.680
<i>And of course he made</i> 
Death of a Ladies' Man,

1:13:30.680 --> 1:13:33.360
<i>um, which, you know,</i>

1:13:33.360 --> 1:13:36.080
<i>is not his best work.</i>

1:13:37.760 --> 1:13:40.360
COHEN:
<i>That happened at a curious time</i>
<i>in my life,</i>

1:13:40.360 --> 1:13:42.960
<i>because I was</i>
<i>at a very low point.</i>

1:13:42.960 --> 1:13:44.720
<i>My family was breaking up.</i>

1:13:44.720 --> 1:13:48.800
<i>I was living in Los Angeles,</i>
<i>which was a foreign city to me.</i>

1:13:48.800 --> 1:13:53.040
<i>And I'd lost control of,</i>
<i>as I say, of my family</i>

1:13:53.040 --> 1:13:55.920
<i>and my work and my life,</i>

1:13:55.920 --> 1:13:58.720
<i>and it was a very,</i>
<i>very dark period.</i>

1:13:58.720 --> 1:14:01.640
<i>And when he got</i>
<i>into the studio,</i>

1:14:01.640 --> 1:14:03.840
<i>it was clear</i>
<i>that he was eccentric,</i>

1:14:03.840 --> 1:14:06.880
<i>but I didn't know</i>
<i>that he was mad.</i>

1:14:06.880 --> 1:14:08.960
<i>The atmosphere was one of guns.</i>

1:14:08.960 --> 1:14:12.400
<i>I mean, that's really</i>
<i>what was going on, was guns.</i>

1:14:12.400 --> 1:14:14.640
<i>The music was a subsidiary.</i>

1:14:14.640 --> 1:14:16.240
<i>People were armed</i>
<i>to the teeth--</i>

1:14:16.240 --> 1:14:18.560
<i>All his friends,</i>
<i>his bodyguards, you know?</i>

1:14:18.560 --> 1:14:20.360
<i>And everybody was drunk.</i>

1:14:20.360 --> 1:14:23.040
<i>So, you know, you were</i>
<i>slipping over bullets.</i>

1:14:23.040 --> 1:14:26.560
<i>You were biting into revolvers</i>
<i>in your hamburger.</i>

1:14:26.560 --> 1:14:28.760
<i>And, I mean,</i>
<i>Phil was beyond control.</i>

1:14:28.760 --> 1:14:33.880
<i>I remember Phil shoved</i>
<i>a revolver into my neck</i>

1:14:33.880 --> 1:14:36.960
<i>and said, you know,</i>
<i>"Leonard, I love you."</i>

1:14:36.960 --> 1:14:39.400
<i>And I said,</i>
<i>"I hope you do, Phil."</i>

1:14:39.400 --> 1:14:42.200
[♪♪♪]

1:14:46.680 --> 1:14:48.520
<i>I think that if anybody, uh--</i>

1:14:48.520 --> 1:14:51.720
<i>Uh, you know, disappointed</i>
<i>the project, it was me.</i>

1:14:51.720 --> 1:14:55.080
<i>I didn't have the chops</i>
<i>to sing those songs.</i>

1:14:55.080 --> 1:14:58.760
<i>I think a song like "Memories"</i>
<i>is a really dynamite tune.</i>

1:14:58.760 --> 1:15:01.360
<i>I think the tune is great,</i>
<i>the lyric is touching.</i>

1:15:01.360 --> 1:15:03.680
<i>I think it really does come out</i>

1:15:03.680 --> 1:15:06.840
<i>of that high-school gymnasium.</i>

1:15:06.840 --> 1:15:10.200
♪ So won't you let me see ♪

1:15:10.200 --> 1:15:12.960
♪ Won't you let me see ♪

1:15:12.960 --> 1:15:16.680
♪ I said
Won't you let me see ♪

1:15:16.680 --> 1:15:19.400
[ALL HARMONIZING]

1:15:21.920 --> 1:15:25.240
♪ Your naked body ♪

1:15:32.080 --> 1:15:35.200
[♪♪♪]

1:15:37.000 --> 1:15:40.920
IHLEN [IN ENGLISH]:
<i>One day, Suzanne,</i>
<i>with little Adam,</i>

1:15:40.920 --> 1:15:44.120
<i>the same age as my son</i>
<i>when I came back to Hydra,</i>

1:15:44.120 --> 1:15:46.400
<i>was standing on the doorway...</i>

1:15:48.480 --> 1:15:52.160
<i>wondering when I was moving out</i>
<i>so she could move in.</i>

1:15:54.720 --> 1:15:56.560
<i>I remember that...</i>

1:15:57.760 --> 1:16:00.880
<i>seeing her, I somehow felt</i>

1:16:00.880 --> 1:16:04.320
<i>a little bit taller,</i>
<i>a little bit stronger,</i>

1:16:04.320 --> 1:16:06.720
<i>a little bit older,</i>
<i>and a little bit wiser.</i>

1:16:06.720 --> 1:16:08.480
<i>[CHUCKLES]</i>

1:16:08.480 --> 1:16:12.280
<i>I got hold of something when</i>
<i>I saw her there with the baby.</i>

1:16:12.280 --> 1:16:16.200
<i>And then</i>
<i>I very calmly packed up,</i>

1:16:16.200 --> 1:16:19.280
<i>took Axel and moved out.</i>

1:16:23.080 --> 1:16:24.440
[SIGHS]

1:16:24.440 --> 1:16:26.560
Yeah, so that was
Marianne finally deciding

1:16:26.560 --> 1:16:29.520
that enough was enough and she
did have to go back to Oslo.

1:16:29.520 --> 1:16:31.920
Her mother had always
wanted her to--

1:16:31.920 --> 1:16:34.760
Wanted her to come here
and have a normal life,

1:16:34.760 --> 1:16:37.400
become a secretary,
a receptionist

1:16:37.400 --> 1:16:40.200
or something like that
and be normal.

1:16:40.200 --> 1:16:41.720
So Marianne had finally decided,

1:16:41.720 --> 1:16:43.320
"Yeah,
that's what I'm gonna do."

1:16:43.320 --> 1:16:46.680
<i>So she came back up here,</i>
<i>became a secretary,</i>

1:16:46.680 --> 1:16:48.440
<i>married a Norwegian man,</i>

1:16:48.440 --> 1:16:52.600
<i>and, um, became a stepmother</i>
<i>to his children.</i>

1:16:52.600 --> 1:16:55.680
<i>Had a very average,</i>
<i>ordinary life.</i>

1:16:55.680 --> 1:16:58.600
<i>And then every once in a while,</i>
<i>she would go back to Hydra</i>

1:16:58.600 --> 1:17:00.480
<i>and visit her friends.</i>

1:17:08.440 --> 1:17:11.080
LISSAUER:
<i>Out of the blue,</i>
<i>and I told you I was--</i>

1:17:11.080 --> 1:17:14.600
<i>I'd done</i> Rebecca<i> and never</i>
<i>heard from Leonard again.</i>

1:17:14.600 --> 1:17:16.360
<i>I thought,</i>
<i>"Well, I did something.</i>

1:17:16.360 --> 1:17:18.280
<i>What did--? I did something."</i>

1:17:18.280 --> 1:17:21.640
<i>He calls up,</i>
<i>"Hey, man. How you doing?"</i>

1:17:21.640 --> 1:17:25.240
1984. "Want to make a record?"

1:17:25.240 --> 1:17:27.320
I'm saying, "Yeah, I've been--

1:17:27.320 --> 1:17:30.000
I've been waiting--
Waiting for this phone call."

1:17:30.000 --> 1:17:31.840
So we went in the studio,

1:17:31.840 --> 1:17:34.400
<i>and we did "Hallelujah"</i>
<i>fairly early.</i>

1:17:34.400 --> 1:17:36.920
<i>And he played it for me,</i>
<i>and it went...</i>

1:17:36.920 --> 1:17:38.760
[PLAYING "HALLELUJAH" MELODY]

1:17:38.760 --> 1:17:43.120
<i>He had just bought</i>
<i>a little Casio synthesizer</i>

1:17:43.120 --> 1:17:45.200
<i>on Seventh Avenue</i>
<i>and 49th Street,</i>

1:17:45.200 --> 1:17:47.000
<i>one of these</i>
<i>"dink-a-dink-a-dink"</i>

1:17:47.000 --> 1:17:49.840
<i>one-finger things,</i>
<i>and he fell in love with it.</i>

1:17:49.840 --> 1:17:52.880
<i>He said, "I want to record</i>
<i>this, use it for the track."</i>

1:17:52.880 --> 1:17:55.560
<i>So we put it down that way.</i>

1:17:55.560 --> 1:17:58.200
<i>We're saying, "Holy crap, man.</i>
<i>This is really good.</i>

1:17:58.200 --> 1:18:00.320
<i>We've done something here."</i>

1:18:00.320 --> 1:18:02.960
<i>Leonard was just grinning.</i>

1:18:02.960 --> 1:18:04.680
<i>Even Marty, who was reluctant</i>

1:18:04.680 --> 1:18:06.480
<i>to like anything</i>
<i>I was involved in,</i>

1:18:06.480 --> 1:18:08.640
<i>just said to us, "This is it."</i>

1:18:10.200 --> 1:18:11.840
<i>We bring him up to Columbia.</i>

1:18:11.840 --> 1:18:14.760
<i>There's a new guy</i>
<i>named Walter Yetnikoff.</i>

1:18:14.760 --> 1:18:17.960
<i>This was his first big thing.</i>
<i>He hears it, and he says,</i>

1:18:17.960 --> 1:18:19.680
<i>"No, I don't like this at all."</i>

1:18:19.680 --> 1:18:22.600
<i>And there's a famous quote,</i>
<i>"Leonard, I know you're great,</i>

1:18:22.600 --> 1:18:24.440
<i>but I don't know</i>
<i>if you're any good."</i>

1:18:24.440 --> 1:18:27.160
<i>Something like that.</i>
<i>And he says,</i>

1:18:27.160 --> 1:18:28.720
<i>"We're not gonna release it."</i>

1:18:28.720 --> 1:18:31.280
And Marty then later says,

1:18:31.280 --> 1:18:34.520
"John, I knew it.
You ruined Leonard's career.

1:18:34.520 --> 1:18:36.920
You have ruined-- This is
an unreleasable record.

1:18:36.920 --> 1:18:39.120
It's the biggest
disappointment in our lives.

1:18:39.120 --> 1:18:40.880
I can't believe
you'd do this to Leonard."

1:18:40.880 --> 1:18:43.200
And he had loved it
earlier in the day, but...

1:18:43.200 --> 1:18:45.840
And I'm saying,
"Well, what do you mean?"

1:18:45.840 --> 1:18:49.960
He said, "No, they hate it.
They're not gonna release it."

1:18:49.960 --> 1:18:51.720
At which point
he ceremoniously

1:18:51.720 --> 1:18:54.360
threw my contract
in the garbage.

1:18:54.360 --> 1:18:56.720
I never got to sign it.
And he said,

1:18:56.720 --> 1:18:59.880
"And you're not gonna be
working for Columbia anymore."

1:18:59.880 --> 1:19:02.800
There was a couple other artists
I was supposed to work with.

1:19:02.800 --> 1:19:05.720
And I was just--
That was it. I was done.

1:19:05.720 --> 1:19:07.720
In the morning,
we thought we had

1:19:07.720 --> 1:19:09.920
this greatest
of all Leonard Cohen records,

1:19:09.920 --> 1:19:12.640
and by the afternoon,
I was out of the business.

1:19:14.520 --> 1:19:16.840
<i>It was the end of the world.</i>

1:19:16.840 --> 1:19:20.600
<i>That's when the whole</i>
<i>Mt. Baldy thing happened.</i>

1:19:20.600 --> 1:19:25.160
<i>That's a huge phase</i>
<i>in Leonard's life.</i>

1:19:25.160 --> 1:19:27.600
<i>I didn't see him. I got</i>
<i>out of the record business</i>

1:19:27.600 --> 1:19:31.800
<i>essentially because of</i>
<i>how this record went down.</i>

1:19:33.880 --> 1:19:37.760
♪ Yes, and I've seen your flag ♪

1:19:37.760 --> 1:19:40.400
♪ On the marble arch ♪

1:19:40.400 --> 1:19:45.440
♪ But love is not
A victory march ♪

1:19:45.440 --> 1:19:50.120
♪ It's a cold
And it's a broken ♪

1:19:50.120 --> 1:19:51.920
♪ Hallelujah... ♪

1:19:51.920 --> 1:19:55.000
LISSAUER:
<i>This record</i>
<i>was monumentally important.</i>

1:19:55.000 --> 1:19:58.320
<i>It was the anthem of anthems.</i>

1:19:58.320 --> 1:20:00.920
<i>But to this day,</i>
<i>I've yet to see any royalties.</i>

1:20:00.920 --> 1:20:04.120
[♪♪♪]

1:20:09.280 --> 1:20:13.320
GOLDMAN:
<i>I think that through all of</i>
<i>this searching and searching</i>

1:20:13.320 --> 1:20:15.640
<i>for herself</i>
<i>and for her identity</i>

1:20:15.640 --> 1:20:19.440
<i>through all those years</i>
<i>on Hydra and other places,</i>

1:20:19.440 --> 1:20:22.040
<i>and having had, you know,</i>
<i>the first husband,</i>

1:20:22.040 --> 1:20:24.240
<i>who was the writer,</i>
<i>and the second husband,</i>

1:20:24.240 --> 1:20:26.560
<i>who was the writer and singer,</i>

1:20:26.560 --> 1:20:28.680
<i>and never really</i>
<i>knowing who she was,</i>

1:20:28.680 --> 1:20:32.080
<i>except in comparison to them</i>
<i>or somehow in relation to them,</i>

1:20:32.080 --> 1:20:34.440
<i>I think it took</i>
<i>coming back here</i>

1:20:34.440 --> 1:20:37.080
<i>for her to really find herself.</i>

1:20:37.080 --> 1:20:42.120
<i>She was a really nice person.</i>
<i>Very kind and very generous.</i>

1:20:42.120 --> 1:20:44.480
She really listened to you
when you talked.

1:20:44.480 --> 1:20:46.640
Not a lot of people do that.

1:20:46.640 --> 1:20:48.640
Most people,
when they're talking to you,

1:20:48.640 --> 1:20:52.240
they're just waiting till
they can say their next line.

1:20:52.240 --> 1:20:55.000
But she was really interested,
and she really listened,

1:20:55.000 --> 1:20:56.240
and she really thought about it.

1:20:56.240 --> 1:20:59.160
<i>She was a very generous</i>
<i>and kind person.</i>

1:21:03.120 --> 1:21:06.440
BROOMFIELD:
<i>I hadn't visited Hydra</i>
<i>for 40 years.</i>

1:21:06.440 --> 1:21:08.360
<i>It had changed</i>
<i>from the wondrous place</i>

1:21:08.360 --> 1:21:10.680
<i>you could live</i>
<i>on a thousand dollars a year</i>

1:21:10.680 --> 1:21:13.400
<i>to the playground</i>
<i>of the very rich.</i>

1:21:16.960 --> 1:21:20.520
<i>One of the only survivors</i>
<i>of the old Hydra is Don Lowe,</i>

1:21:20.520 --> 1:21:22.960
<i>who lives up this path,</i>
<i>in this house</i>

1:21:22.960 --> 1:21:25.760
<i>without electricity</i>
<i>or running water.</i>

1:21:25.760 --> 1:21:29.440
<i>Don prefers candles</i>
<i>and has a well.</i>

1:21:29.440 --> 1:21:32.920
<i>Marianne introduced me</i>
<i>to Don in 1968.</i>

1:21:32.920 --> 1:21:36.480
<i>He has since self-published</i>
<i>over 30 books.</i>

1:21:37.560 --> 1:21:39.280
BROOMFIELD:
Oh, there you are.

1:21:39.280 --> 1:21:41.520
LOWE: Let me come out.
[CHUCKLES]

1:21:43.280 --> 1:21:46.400
<i>Don has lived</i>
<i>on Hydra for 60 years.</i>

1:21:46.400 --> 1:21:50.280
<i>The last time he left</i>
<i>the island was 25 years ago.</i>

1:21:50.280 --> 1:21:52.320
I made this for my--

1:21:52.320 --> 1:21:55.760
Anyone who gets stuck and they
got nowhere to live, you see?

1:21:55.760 --> 1:21:57.400
So--
Wow, it's beautiful.

1:21:57.400 --> 1:22:00.240
It's nice, you see? Dug it out.

1:22:00.240 --> 1:22:02.040
Did one of your children
do that?

1:22:02.040 --> 1:22:04.600
LOWE: No, I did that.
You did that? It's beautiful.

1:22:04.600 --> 1:22:07.040
That's my idea of paradise.

1:22:07.040 --> 1:22:10.240
You can cook here
and you can write a book here,

1:22:10.240 --> 1:22:12.160
if you are that way inclined.

1:22:12.160 --> 1:22:15.000
It's got a view...

1:22:15.000 --> 1:22:16.680
of the sea and next door--

1:22:16.680 --> 1:22:20.880
This is where Marianne was
gonna stay, in the house there.

1:22:20.880 --> 1:22:23.040
Marianne was gonna stay
where? In the house?

1:22:23.040 --> 1:22:26.920
Just there.
You can see it through there.

1:22:26.920 --> 1:22:29.320
She was very nice
at the end, Marianne.

1:22:29.320 --> 1:22:32.320
Because she mellowed,
and, you know.

1:22:32.320 --> 1:22:34.920
'Cause it was never easy
after Leonard,

1:22:34.920 --> 1:22:37.400
'cause every time he gave
a concert or something,

1:22:37.400 --> 1:22:39.960
she'd get caught up in it.

1:22:39.960 --> 1:22:42.680
Every time he gave--?
Every time he gave a concert,

1:22:42.680 --> 1:22:45.680
she had an invitation,
and she was interviewed

1:22:45.680 --> 1:22:49.480
in Norway and things like that,
and so she couldn't really--

1:22:49.480 --> 1:22:52.080
She married
a lovely guy afterwards,

1:22:52.080 --> 1:22:55.400
divorced him and married
him again, and, uh--

1:22:55.400 --> 1:22:57.080
Jan. A very sweet man.

1:22:57.080 --> 1:22:58.600
Norwegian.

1:22:59.840 --> 1:23:01.840
Uh, but, yeah, I was--

1:23:01.840 --> 1:23:04.320
Got quite fond of her
at the end, Marianne.

1:23:04.320 --> 1:23:09.240
When we were younger,
we lived our own way.

1:23:09.240 --> 1:23:13.040
But at the end,
she became very close.

1:23:13.040 --> 1:23:14.560
Mm-hmm.

1:23:16.400 --> 1:23:18.760
[BELL CHIMES]

1:23:18.760 --> 1:23:21.360
[RINGING]

1:23:30.240 --> 1:23:32.600
[ALL CHANTING INDISTINCTLY]

1:23:38.000 --> 1:23:41.080
COHEN:
<i>I had some wonderful moments</i>
<i>on the road,</i>

1:23:41.080 --> 1:23:42.840
<i>you know,</i>
<i>traveling with musicians</i>

1:23:42.840 --> 1:23:44.240
<i>and playing with musicians.</i>

1:23:44.240 --> 1:23:45.720
<i>But, by and large,</i>

1:23:45.720 --> 1:23:47.600
<i>I didn't have what it took</i>

1:23:47.600 --> 1:23:51.760
<i>to really enjoy my success</i>
<i>or my celebrity.</i>

1:23:51.760 --> 1:23:53.800
<i>I was never able to locate it.</i>

1:23:53.800 --> 1:23:56.400
<i>I was never able to use it.</i>

1:23:59.760 --> 1:24:01.120
That's beautiful, huh?

1:24:01.120 --> 1:24:03.040
CORNELIUS:
<i>Doing what he did up there</i>

1:24:03.040 --> 1:24:04.320
<i>came natural to him</i>

1:24:04.320 --> 1:24:06.120
<i>because of his discipline.</i>

1:24:06.120 --> 1:24:10.080
<i>He became a servant</i>
<i>for years and years there.</i>

1:24:10.080 --> 1:24:12.680
<i>He had to get up, like,</i>
<i>at 3:00 in the morning.</i>

1:24:12.680 --> 1:24:15.440
<i>Some of the things he told me</i>
<i>that they did up there,</i>

1:24:15.440 --> 1:24:18.400
<i>I don't know if</i>
<i>I could've hung with that.</i>

1:24:18.400 --> 1:24:19.640
You a small?
Yeah.

1:24:19.640 --> 1:24:21.320
You're a black bag?
Yeah.

1:24:21.320 --> 1:24:23.280
Uh, brown bag.
What did I do with it?

1:24:23.280 --> 1:24:25.440
Oh, in here, Roshi. In here.
Oh.

1:24:25.440 --> 1:24:26.840
In here.

1:24:29.120 --> 1:24:31.840
My handbag here?
Your handbag?

1:24:31.840 --> 1:24:33.240
Yeah.
It's still in the car?

1:24:33.240 --> 1:24:34.880
Yeah.
Oh, okay.

1:24:36.480 --> 1:24:38.200
Want to eat something, Roshi?
Eh?

1:24:38.200 --> 1:24:39.880
You want to eat something?

1:24:39.880 --> 1:24:41.640
[SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY]

1:24:41.640 --> 1:24:43.080
Oh, okay. Okay.

1:24:43.080 --> 1:24:46.680
LISSAUER:
<i>Roshi was</i>
<i>his spiritual adviser,</i>

1:24:46.680 --> 1:24:49.640
<i>his Buddhist monk leader.</i>

1:24:49.640 --> 1:24:52.560
<i>He centered him.</i>
<i>It was like having</i>

1:24:52.560 --> 1:24:54.640
<i>Mom and Dad watching you</i>

1:24:54.640 --> 1:24:59.400
<i>if you think you're likely</i>
<i>to be tempted to stray.</i>

1:24:59.400 --> 1:25:01.440
<i>I think it was his crutch.</i>

1:25:01.440 --> 1:25:05.560
<i>And it also probably increased</i>
<i>his focus and concentration.</i>

1:25:05.560 --> 1:25:09.200
COHEN:
<i>I'm trying to learn</i>
<i>some things about love.</i>

1:25:12.440 --> 1:25:16.240
Well, love is
that activity that...

1:25:16.240 --> 1:25:20.520
That makes the power
of man and woman...

1:25:20.520 --> 1:25:24.400
that incorporates it
into your own heart,

1:25:24.400 --> 1:25:27.000
where you can embody
man and woman,

1:25:27.000 --> 1:25:29.760
when you can embody
hell and heaven,

1:25:29.760 --> 1:25:32.440
when you can reconcile
and contain,

1:25:32.440 --> 1:25:36.280
when man and woman
becomes your content.

1:25:36.280 --> 1:25:38.320
In other words,
when your woman

1:25:38.320 --> 1:25:40.720
becomes your own content,

1:25:40.720 --> 1:25:44.520
and you become her content,
that's love.

1:25:45.920 --> 1:25:47.760
And-- And you recognize

1:25:47.760 --> 1:25:50.320
the full equality
of that exchange,

1:25:50.320 --> 1:25:53.800
because if she's smaller
than you, she can't fill you.

1:25:53.800 --> 1:25:57.600
And if you're larger than her,
you can't fill her.

1:25:57.600 --> 1:25:59.760
You know? So there
has to be an understanding

1:25:59.760 --> 1:26:03.320
that there really is
an absolute equality of power.

1:26:03.320 --> 1:26:05.160
Different kinds of power.
Obvious--

1:26:05.160 --> 1:26:07.240
Obviously
different kinds of magic.

1:26:07.240 --> 1:26:11.320
Different kinds of strength,
different kinds of movement,

1:26:11.320 --> 1:26:14.080
that's as different
as night and day.

1:26:14.080 --> 1:26:17.560
And it is night and day.
And it is the moon and the sun.

1:26:17.560 --> 1:26:20.680
And it is the land and the sea.
And it is plus and minus.

1:26:20.680 --> 1:26:23.720
It is heaven and hell.
It is all those antonyms.

1:26:23.720 --> 1:26:25.400
But they're all equal.

1:26:26.840 --> 1:26:29.680
<i>I have experienced it.</i>
<i>I have experienced it.</i>

1:26:29.680 --> 1:26:31.480
<i>You don't</i>
<i>have to change the world.</i>

1:26:31.480 --> 1:26:34.200
<i>There doesn't have to be</i>
<i>any revolutions.</i>

1:26:44.800 --> 1:26:47.200
CORNELIUS:
<i>I'm sure that</i>
<i>everybody already knows</i>

1:26:47.200 --> 1:26:50.480
<i>about all that, uh,</i>
<i>transpired along the way</i>

1:26:50.480 --> 1:26:52.520
when he came back down
off the mountain.

1:26:52.520 --> 1:26:54.320
He had no money, you know?

1:26:54.320 --> 1:26:58.040
Because this person
that he had trusted,

1:26:58.040 --> 1:27:00.920
a person that he would
have taken a bullet for,

1:27:00.920 --> 1:27:04.360
so to speak,
that's what he told me,

1:27:04.360 --> 1:27:06.360
<i>that he spent holidays with,</i>

1:27:06.360 --> 1:27:08.880
<i>with her children</i>
<i>and his children,</i>

1:27:08.880 --> 1:27:12.240
<i>had absolutely sold him out.</i>

1:27:12.240 --> 1:27:16.120
<i>And that it turned out</i>
<i>that a friendship</i>

1:27:16.120 --> 1:27:19.280
<i>that he thought</i>
<i>was the real deal</i>

1:27:19.280 --> 1:27:23.960
<i>ended up being</i>
<i>a really bad thing.</i>

1:27:23.960 --> 1:27:27.240
COHEN:
<i>Well, the money</i>
<i>seems to be gone.</i>

1:27:27.240 --> 1:27:30.360
As far as the manager,

1:27:30.360 --> 1:27:33.000
you know,
who was my dear friend...

1:27:34.760 --> 1:27:36.560
I'm still rather fond of her.

1:27:36.560 --> 1:27:39.280
But, uh, she, um--

1:27:39.280 --> 1:27:42.400
There's been a-- A judgment of--

1:27:42.400 --> 1:27:45.000
Of several million dollars
against her.

1:27:45.000 --> 1:27:47.920
But, you know, that's--

1:27:47.920 --> 1:27:49.680
She doesn't
seem to have any money,

1:27:49.680 --> 1:27:52.120
so it's impossible
to collect it.

1:27:52.120 --> 1:27:54.920
I don't know. I guess I should
be more worried than I am,

1:27:54.920 --> 1:27:57.480
but I'm not. So, what can I say?

1:27:57.480 --> 1:27:58.960
Heh-heh, you know?

1:27:58.960 --> 1:28:01.040
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING, CHEERING]

1:28:07.440 --> 1:28:10.400
CORNELIUS:
<i>All of a sudden, here he is.</i>

1:28:10.400 --> 1:28:13.600
<i>He's now in his 70s,</i>

1:28:13.600 --> 1:28:15.840
<i>and he has no money now.</i>

1:28:15.840 --> 1:28:19.640
<i>He said to me, "All I can do</i>
<i>is get out there and tour</i>

1:28:19.640 --> 1:28:21.440
<i>and try to make some money."</i>

1:28:21.440 --> 1:28:24.200
<i>He said, "I don't know</i>
<i>if I can do it or not."</i>

1:28:24.200 --> 1:28:27.360
It's, uh--
It's been a long time

1:28:27.360 --> 1:28:30.160
since I stood
on a stage in London.

1:28:30.160 --> 1:28:32.480
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

1:28:33.920 --> 1:28:35.920
It was about, uh--

1:28:35.920 --> 1:28:38.560
About, uh, 14 or 15 years ago.

1:28:38.560 --> 1:28:41.560
I was 60 years old.

1:28:41.560 --> 1:28:43.720
Just a kid with a crazy dream.

1:28:43.720 --> 1:28:45.960
[AUDIENCE LAUGHS]

1:28:45.960 --> 1:28:48.960
LISSAUER:
<i>Suddenly, Leonard was</i>
<i>the hottest ticket in town,</i>

1:28:48.960 --> 1:28:51.040
<i>and he went from</i>
<i>our little tour bus</i>

1:28:51.040 --> 1:28:54.040
<i>with two sound engineers</i>
<i>and three roadies</i>

1:28:54.040 --> 1:28:57.280
<i>to an entourage of 59 people</i>
<i>on his own jet.</i>

1:28:57.280 --> 1:29:01.600
♪ Show me slowly
What I only know ♪

1:29:01.600 --> 1:29:04.040
♪ The limits of ♪

1:29:04.040 --> 1:29:06.600
♪ And dance me ♪

1:29:06.600 --> 1:29:09.240
♪ To the end of love... ♪

1:29:09.240 --> 1:29:13.760
<i>And he was making upwards</i>
<i>of $15 million every year.</i>

1:29:13.760 --> 1:29:16.200
<i>One of the top-ten</i>
<i>grossing acts.</i>

1:29:16.200 --> 1:29:19.560
<i>He went from literally</i>
<i>being wiped out</i>

1:29:19.560 --> 1:29:21.640
<i>to incredible stardom.</i>

1:29:21.640 --> 1:29:24.160
[ALL CHEERING]

1:29:27.080 --> 1:29:30.240
[BAND STARTS PLAYING
"SO LONG, MARIANNE"]

1:29:50.920 --> 1:29:55.320
♪ So long, Marianne ♪

1:29:55.320 --> 1:29:58.320
♪ It's time that we began ♪

1:29:58.320 --> 1:30:02.160
♪ To laugh and cry ♪

1:30:02.160 --> 1:30:04.360
♪ And cry ♪

1:30:04.360 --> 1:30:07.800
♪ And laugh
About it all again... ♪

1:30:07.800 --> 1:30:09.880
MOLLESTAD:
<i>It was a love story</i>

1:30:09.880 --> 1:30:12.840
<i>which had 50 chapters</i>

1:30:12.840 --> 1:30:14.880
<i>without being together.</i>

1:30:14.880 --> 1:30:16.520
<i>[LAUGHS]</i>

1:30:16.520 --> 1:30:19.920
<i>She had a compartment</i>
<i>of her heart</i>

1:30:19.920 --> 1:30:23.200
<i>which was</i>
<i>always married to Leonard.</i>

1:30:29.080 --> 1:30:31.400
That's the beauty

1:30:31.400 --> 1:30:34.400
of Marianne's
and Leonard's history,

1:30:34.400 --> 1:30:37.600
that they had this place
for each other,

1:30:37.600 --> 1:30:41.000
uh, till the very end.

1:30:41.000 --> 1:30:44.560
And it's not the bitter end.
It was a lovely end.

1:30:44.560 --> 1:30:47.040
It's a very beautiful end.

1:30:47.040 --> 1:30:51.160
<i>Suddenly one evening,</i>
<i>I got an SMS saying,</i>

1:30:51.160 --> 1:30:54.960
<i>"I'm at hospital.</i>
<i>I'm going to die.</i>

1:30:54.960 --> 1:30:57.560
<i>Please take care</i>
<i>of Little Axel</i>

1:30:57.560 --> 1:31:00.400
<i>and Jan, my husband."</i>

1:31:00.400 --> 1:31:02.320
She asked me,

1:31:02.320 --> 1:31:05.400
"Could you--
Could you tell Leonard?"

1:31:07.560 --> 1:31:11.320
And another thing she said was,
"Could you bring a camera?

1:31:11.320 --> 1:31:14.640
Because I still feel
I have something to say."

1:31:14.640 --> 1:31:16.840
[♪♪♪]

1:31:18.880 --> 1:31:22.040
<i>And in the morning,</i>
<i>there was this lovely letter</i>

1:31:22.040 --> 1:31:24.800
<i>from Leonard to Marianne.</i>

1:31:27.960 --> 1:31:29.920
"Dearest Marianne...

1:31:32.000 --> 1:31:35.600
I'm just a little behind you.

1:31:35.600 --> 1:31:38.440
Close enough
to take your hand.

1:31:40.160 --> 1:31:43.320
This old body of mine
has given up,

1:31:43.320 --> 1:31:46.000
as yours has too.

1:31:46.000 --> 1:31:50.880
I've never forgotten
your love and your beauty...

1:31:50.880 --> 1:31:53.000
but you know that.

1:31:53.000 --> 1:31:56.080
I don't have to say more.

1:31:56.080 --> 1:31:59.320
Safe travels, old friend.

1:31:59.320 --> 1:32:02.000
See you down the road.

1:32:02.000 --> 1:32:05.680
Endless love and gratitude,

1:32:05.680 --> 1:32:07.680
your Leonard."

1:32:09.880 --> 1:32:12.200
[IN ENGLISH]
That was very beautiful.

1:32:15.960 --> 1:32:17.280
Very beautiful.

1:32:17.280 --> 1:32:19.160
MOLLESTAD:
Very beautiful.

1:32:19.160 --> 1:32:21.160
Yeah.

1:32:22.440 --> 1:32:25.000
[IN NORWEGIAN]
If only he was as lucky as me,

1:32:25.000 --> 1:32:26.800
getting his feet
massaged by Sue.

1:32:26.800 --> 1:32:29.480
[BOTH LAUGHING]

1:32:29.480 --> 1:32:33.600
[MARIANNE SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY
IN NORWEGIAN]

1:32:33.600 --> 1:32:35.760
[MOLLESTAD CHUCKLING]

1:32:43.320 --> 1:32:45.840
And the beautiful thing
was that

1:32:45.840 --> 1:32:50.320
this old, sick man...

1:32:50.320 --> 1:32:56.400
reached his old, sick lover...

1:32:58.720 --> 1:33:01.480
with a message that, uh...

1:33:02.840 --> 1:33:05.680
she had always wanted to hear.

1:33:07.640 --> 1:33:09.000
And...

1:33:10.320 --> 1:33:13.680
I think that, uh...

1:33:13.680 --> 1:33:17.440
for Marianne, this was a ring

1:33:17.440 --> 1:33:19.880
that started with leaving Oslo

1:33:19.880 --> 1:33:22.280
<i>and going into</i>
<i>the adventure with Axel</i>

1:33:22.280 --> 1:33:25.840
<i>and meeting Leonard,</i>

1:33:25.840 --> 1:33:28.280
<i>losing Leonard,</i>

1:33:28.280 --> 1:33:30.280
<i>meeting Jan...</i>

1:33:32.080 --> 1:33:34.960
<i>having problems,</i>
<i>of course, with her son.</i>

1:33:37.080 --> 1:33:41.760
And then when this love letter
came from Leonard...

1:33:41.760 --> 1:33:45.960
I think she felt
that it was all completed.

1:33:47.240 --> 1:33:49.120
So, uh...

1:33:52.200 --> 1:33:55.880
